{"title_page": "Timeline of the Donald Trump presidency (2020 Q2)", "text_new": "{{short description|Wikimedia list article}}\n{{use mdy dates|date=December 2019}}\n{{Donald Trump series}}\n\nThe following is a [[timeline]] of the [[presidency of Donald Trump]] during the second quarter of 2020. To navigate quarters, see [[Timeline of the Donald Trump presidency]].\n\n\n{{TOC left}}\n{{clear}}<!-- Avoid layout clash between sidebar and April table. Eventually a longer lead section will help fill the empty space. -->\n\n==Timeline==\n===Overview===\n\nPresident Trump faced the ongoing presidential primaries and the ongoing coronavirus pandemic by extending the nationwide [[Centers for Disease Control and Prevention]] guidelines throughout the month of April. <ref>{{cite web |title=Remarks by President Trump, Vice President Pence, and Members of the Coronavirus Task Force in Press Briefing |url=https://www.whitehouse.gov/briefings-statements/remarks-president-trump-vice-president-pence-members-coronavirus-task-force-press-briefing-16/ |website=whitehouse.gov |accessdate=3 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n===April 2020===\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Date\n! Events\n! Photos/Videos\n|- style=\"background:white;\"\n| colspan=\"3\" |\n\n====Week 166====\n\n|-\n| Wednesday, '''April 1'''\n|\n* President Trump reveals that his decision to extend the social distancing guidelines to April 30 was motivated by models which predicted that if the restrictions were removed as many as 2.2 million people would die and around half of the country would be infected.<ref>{{cite web|title=Trump's coronavirus team to reveal sobering data that drove decision to extend restrictions|url=https://abcnews.go.com/Politics/trumps-coronavirus-team-reveal-sobering-data-drove-decision/story|last1=Phelps|first1=Jordyn|last2=Gittleson|first2=Ben|publisher=ABC News|date=March 31, 2020|accessdate=March 31, 2020}}</ref> President Trump also warned that between 100,000 and 240,000 Americans could become infected in the coming days, despite strict isolation and distancing guidelines.<ref>{{cite web|title=Trump's alarming message portends tragic days ahead|url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/03/31/politics/trump-coronavirus/index.html|last=Collinson|first=Stephen|publisher=CNN|date=April 1, 2020|accessdate=April 1, 2020}}</ref>\n* The number of deaths in the United States from the coronavirus disease is 4,394. One thousand nine hundred and forty one are in New York state, two hundred and sixty seven in New Jersey, two hundred and fifty nine in Michigan, two hundred and thirty nine in Louisiana, two hundred and twenty five in Washington state, one hundred and eighty four in California and one hundred and thirty nine in Georgia. Every other state except for Wyoming has at least one death attributed to the virus.<ref name=\"US Covid-19 Stats\">{{cite web |title=Coronavirus Dashboard |url=https://ncov2019.live/data |accessdate=1 April 2020}}</ref>\n|\n|-\n| Thursday, '''April 2'''\n|\n* [[Thomas Modly|Acting Secretary of the Navy Thomas Modly]] announced he had relieved Navy Captain [[Brett Crozier]] of command of the coronavirus-stricken [[USS Theodore Roosevelt (CVN-71)|USS Theodore Roosevelt]], for going outside the chain of command and seeking help with the 114 positive coronavirus cases onboard the aircraft carrier.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-us-canada-52145230|title=US Navy removes captain who raised virus alarm|date=April 3, 2020|work=BBC News|access-date=April 3, 2020|language=en-GB}}</ref> \n|\n|-\n| Friday, '''April 3'''\n|\n* President Trump notifies Congress that he had \"removed from office\" [[Michael Atkinson (Inspector General)|Intelligence Community Inspector General Michael Atkinson]], the individual who had informed Congress about the whistleblower complaint that led to the Ukraine probe and the president's impeachment.<ref>{{cite news |first1=Natasha |last1=Bertrand |first2=Andrew |last2=Desiderio |url=https://www.politico.com/news/2020/04/03/trump-fires-intelligence-community-inspector-general-164287 |title=Trump fires intelligence community inspector general who defied him on Ukraine |website=[[Politico]] |language=en |access-date=2020-04-04 |date=2020-04-03}}</ref>\n|\n[[File:NEXT- Press briefing with the Coronavirus Task Force at 5-00 p.m. ET..webm|thumb|center|upright=0.8|start=25:25|President Trump and members of the coronavirus task force hold a news conference (April 3, 2020)]]\n|-\n| Saturday, '''April 4'''\n|\n* \n|\n|-\n| Sunday, '''April 5'''\n|\n*\n|\n|- style=\"background:white;\"\n| colspan=\"3\" |\n\n====Week 167====\n\n|-\n| Monday, '''April 6'''\n|\n*\n|\n|-\n| Tuesday, '''April 7'''\n|\n* President Trump announces that [[Kayleigh McEnany]] will become the 31st White House Press Secretary, replacing Stephanie Grisham, who was moved to be the First Lady's Chief of Staff.<ref>{{cite web|title=Trump Has a New Press Secretary: Kayleigh McEnany, a Campaign Spokeswoman|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/04/07/us/politics/kayleigh-mcenany-stephanie-grisham-trump.html|last=Haberman|first=Maggie|publisher=The New York Times|date=April 7, 2020|accessdate=April 7, 2020}}</ref>\n* President Trump replaces [[Glenn A. Fine]], acting inspector general for the Defense Department and chairman of the recently created Pandemic Response Accountability Committee, with Sean O\u2019Donnell, the Environmental Protection Agency\u2019s inspector general.\n*  Acting Navy Secretary [[Thomas Modly]] submits a letter of resignation to Defense Secretary Mark Esper.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Sciutto |first1=Jim |last2=Starr |first2=Barbara |last3=Cohen |first3=Zachary |title=Acting secretary of the Navy resigns after calling ousted aircraft carrier captain 'stupid' |url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/04/07/politics/modly-resign-crozier-esper-trump/index.html |accessdate=7 April 2020 |publisher=CNN |date=April 7, 2020}}</ref>\n|\n|-\n| Wednesday, '''April 8'''\n|\n*\n|\n|-\n| Thursday, '''April 9'''\n|\n* \n|\n|-\n| Friday, '''April 10'''\n|\n*\n|\n|-\n| Saturday, '''April 11'''\n|\n* \n|\n|-\n| Sunday, '''April 12'''\n|\n*\n|\n|}<!--\n|- style=\"background:white;\"\n| colspan=\"3\" |\n\n====Week 168====\n\n|-\n| Monday, '''April 13'''\n|\n*\n|\n|-\n| Tuesday, '''April 14'''\n|\n* \n|\n|-\n| Wednesday, '''April 15'''\n|\n*\n|\n|-\n| Thursday, '''April 16'''\n|\n* \n|\n|-\n| Friday, '''April 17'''\n|\n*\n|\n|-\n| Saturday, '''April 18'''\n|\n* \n|\n|-\n| Sunday, '''April 19'''\n|\n*\n|\n|}-->\n\n==See also==\n\n{{Wikipedia books\n | 1 = Timeline of the Donald Trump presidency\n}}\n* [[Presidential transition of Donald Trump]]\n* [[First 100 days of Donald Trump's presidency]]\n* [[List of executive actions by Donald Trump]]\n* [[List of presidential trips made by Donald Trump]] ([[List of international presidential trips made by Donald Trump|international trips]])\n\n==References==\n\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-other|[[List of Presidents of the United States|U.S. presidential administration timelines]]}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Timeline of the Donald Trump presidency (2020 Q1)|Trump presidency (2020 Q1)]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Trump presidency (2020 Q2)}}\n{{s-aft|after=Trump presidency (2020 Q3)}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Donald Trump}}\n\n[[Category:Presidency of Donald Trump|*]]\n[[Category:2020 in American politics|Presidency of Donald Trump]]\n[[Category:United States presidency timelines|Trump]]\n[[Category:Timelines of current events|Trump]]\n[[Category:April 2020 events in the United States]]\n[[Category:May 2020 events in the United States]]\n[[Category:June 2020 events in the United States]]\n[[Category:2020-related timelines]]\n[[Category:Political timelines of the 2020s by year]]\n[[Category:Contemporary history of the United States]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Wikimedia list article}}\n{{use mdy dates|date=December 2019}}\n{{Donald Trump series}}\n\nThe following is a [[timeline]] of the [[presidency of Donald Trump]] during the second quarter of 2020. To navigate quarters, see [[Timeline of the Donald Trump presidency]].\n\n\n{{TOC left}}\n{{clear}}<!-- Avoid layout clash between sidebar and April table. Eventually a longer lead section will help fill the empty space. -->\n\n==Timeline==\n===Overview===\n\nPresident Trump faced the ongoing presidential primaries and the ongoing coronavirus pandemic by extending the nationwide [[Centers for Disease Control and Prevention]] guidelines throughout the month of April. <ref>{{cite web |title=Remarks by President Trump, Vice President Pence, and Members of the Coronavirus Task Force in Press Briefing |url=https://www.whitehouse.gov/briefings-statements/remarks-president-trump-vice-president-pence-members-coronavirus-task-force-press-briefing-16/ |website=whitehouse.gov |accessdate=3 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n===April 2020===\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Date\n! Events\n! Photos/Videos\n|- style=\"background:white;\"\n| colspan=\"3\" |\n\n====Week 166====\n\n|-\n| Wednesday, '''April 1'''\n|\n* President Trump reveals that his decision to extend the social distancing guidelines to April 30 was motivated by models which predicted that if the restrictions were removed as many as 2.2 million people would die and around half of the country would be infected.<ref>{{cite web|title=Trump's coronavirus team to reveal sobering data that drove decision to extend restrictions|url=https://abcnews.go.com/Politics/trumps-coronavirus-team-reveal-sobering-data-drove-decision/story|last1=Phelps|first1=Jordyn|last2=Gittleson|first2=Ben|publisher=ABC News|date=March 31, 2020|accessdate=March 31, 2020}}</ref> President Trump also warned that between 100,000 and 240,000 Americans could become infected in the coming days, despite strict isolation and distancing guidelines.<ref>{{cite web|title=Trump's alarming message portends tragic days ahead|url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/03/31/politics/trump-coronavirus/index.html|last=Collinson|first=Stephen|publisher=CNN|date=April 1, 2020|accessdate=April 1, 2020}}</ref>\n* The number of deaths in the United States from the coronavirus disease is 4,394. One thousand nine hundred and forty one are in New York state, two hundred and sixty seven in New Jersey, two hundred and fifty nine in Michigan, two hundred and thirty nine in Louisiana, two hundred and twenty five in Washington state, one hundred and eighty four in California and one hundred and thirty nine in Georgia. Every other state except for Wyoming has at least one death attributed to the virus.<ref name=\"US Covid-19 Stats\">{{cite web |title=Coronavirus Dashboard |url=https://ncov2019.live/data |accessdate=1 April 2020}}</ref>\n|\n|-\n| Thursday, '''April 2'''\n|\n* [[Thomas Modly|Acting Secretary of the Navy Thomas Modly]] announced he had relieved Navy Captain [[Brett Crozier]] of command of the coronavirus-stricken [[USS Theodore Roosevelt (CVN-71)|USS Theodore Roosevelt]], for going outside the chain of command and seeking help with the 114 positive coronavirus cases onboard the aircraft carrier.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-us-canada-52145230|title=US Navy removes captain who raised virus alarm|date=April 3, 2020|work=BBC News|access-date=April 3, 2020|language=en-GB}}</ref> \n|\n|-\n| Friday, '''April 3'''\n|\n* President Trump notifies Congress that he had \"removed from office\" [[Michael Atkinson (Inspector General)|Intelligence Community Inspector General Michael Atkinson]], the individual who had informed Congress about the whistleblower complaint that led to the Ukraine probe and the president's impeachment.<ref>{{cite news |first1=Natasha |last1=Bertrand |first2=Andrew |last2=Desiderio |url=https://www.politico.com/news/2020/04/03/trump-fires-intelligence-community-inspector-general-164287 |title=Trump fires intelligence community inspector general who defied him on Ukraine |website=[[Politico]] |language=en |access-date=2020-04-04 |date=2020-04-03}}</ref>\n|\n[[File:NEXT- Press briefing with the Coronavirus Task Force at 5-00 p.m. ET..webm|thumb|center|upright=0.8|start=25:25|President Trump and members of the coronavirus task force hold a news conference (April 3, 2020)]]\n|-\n| Saturday, '''April 4'''\n|\n* \n|\n|-\n| Sunday, '''April 5'''\n|\n*\n|\n|- style=\"background:white;\"\n| colspan=\"3\" |\n\n====Week 167====\n\n|-\n| Monday, '''April 6'''\n|\n*\n|\n|-\n| Tuesday, '''April 7'''\n|\n* President Trump announces that [[Kayleigh McEnany]] will become the 31st White House Press Secretary, replacing Stephanie Grisham, who was moved to be the First Lady's Chief of Staff.<ref>{{cite web|title=Trump Has a New Press Secretary: Kayleigh McEnany, a Campaign Spokeswoman|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/04/07/us/politics/kayleigh-mcenany-stephanie-grisham-trump.html|last=Haberman|first=Maggie|publisher=The New York Times|date=April 7, 2020|accessdate=April 7, 2020}}</ref>\n* President Trump replaces [[Glenn A. Fine]], acting inspector general for the Defense Department and chairman of the recently created Pandemic Response Accountability Committee, with Sean O\u2019Donnell, the Environmental Protection Agency\u2019s inspector general.\n*  Acting Navy Secretary [[Thomas Modly]] submitts a letter of resignation to Defense Secretary Mark Esper.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Sciutto |first1=Jim |last2=Starr |first2=Barbara |last3=Cohen |first3=Zachary |title=Acting secretary of the Navy resigns after calling ousted aircraft carrier captain 'stupid' |url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/04/07/politics/modly-resign-crozier-esper-trump/index.html |accessdate=7 April 2020 |publisher=CNN |date=April 7, 2020}}</ref>\n|\n|-\n| Wednesday, '''April 8'''\n|\n*\n|\n|-\n| Thursday, '''April 9'''\n|\n* \n|\n|-\n| Friday, '''April 10'''\n|\n*\n|\n|-\n| Saturday, '''April 11'''\n|\n* \n|\n|-\n| Sunday, '''April 12'''\n|\n*\n|\n|}<!--\n|- style=\"background:white;\"\n| colspan=\"3\" |\n\n====Week 168====\n\n|-\n| Monday, '''April 13'''\n|\n*\n|\n|-\n| Tuesday, '''April 14'''\n|\n* \n|\n|-\n| Wednesday, '''April 15'''\n|\n*\n|\n|-\n| Thursday, '''April 16'''\n|\n* \n|\n|-\n| Friday, '''April 17'''\n|\n*\n|\n|-\n| Saturday, '''April 18'''\n|\n* \n|\n|-\n| Sunday, '''April 19'''\n|\n*\n|\n|}-->\n\n==See also==\n\n{{Wikipedia books\n | 1 = Timeline of the Donald Trump presidency\n}}\n* [[Presidential transition of Donald Trump]]\n* [[First 100 days of Donald Trump's presidency]]\n* [[List of executive actions by Donald Trump]]\n* [[List of presidential trips made by Donald Trump]] ([[List of international presidential trips made by Donald Trump|international trips]])\n\n==References==\n\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-other|[[List of Presidents of the United States|U.S. presidential administration timelines]]}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Timeline of the Donald Trump presidency (2020 Q1)|Trump presidency (2020 Q1)]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Trump presidency (2020 Q2)}}\n{{s-aft|after=Trump presidency (2020 Q3)}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Donald Trump}}\n\n[[Category:Presidency of Donald Trump|*]]\n[[Category:2020 in American politics|Presidency of Donald Trump]]\n[[Category:United States presidency timelines|Trump]]\n[[Category:Timelines of current events|Trump]]\n[[Category:April 2020 events in the United States]]\n[[Category:May 2020 events in the United States]]\n[[Category:June 2020 events in the United States]]\n[[Category:2020-related timelines]]\n[[Category:Political timelines of the 2020s by year]]\n[[Category:Contemporary history of the United States]]\n", "name_user": "Diablomarcus", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eWeek 167:Spelling error.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Timeline_of_the_Donald_Trump_presidency_(2020_Q2)"}
{"title_page": "Charles Taylor (Liberian politician)", "text_new": "{{redirect|Charles G. Taylor|the English cricketer|Charles Taylor (cricketer, born 1816)|the Welsh rugby union player|Charles Taylor (rugby union)|the American baseball player|Chuck Taylor (baseball)}}\n{{short description|Liberian former politician who was the 22nd President of Liberia}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2013}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|name          = Colby Keller\n|image         = President Charles Taylor.png\n|birth_name    = Colby McArthur Ghankay Keller\n|office        = 22nd [[President of Liberia]]\n|term_start    = 2 August 1997\n|alt = Taylor seated at a desk\n|term_end      = 11 August 2003\n|vicepresident = {{plainlist|\n*[[Enoch Dogolea]]\n*[[Moses Blah]]}}\n|predecessor   = [[Ruth Perry]] (Chairperson of the Council of State)\n|successor     = [[Moses Blah]]\n|birth_date    = {{Birth date and age|df=yes|1948|1|28}}\n|birth_place   = [[Arthington, Liberia|Arthington]], [[Liberia]]\n|party         = [[People's Redemption Council]] (expelled in 1983) <br>[[National Patriotic Party|National Patriotic]]\n|spouse        = {{ubl|{{marriage|Enid Tupee Taylor|1979|1997}}|{{marriage|[[Jewel Taylor|Jewel Howard]]|1997|2006|end=div}}}}\n|children      = 14, including [[Charles McArther Emmanuel]]\n|alma_mater    = [[Bentley University]] \n|occupation = [[Warlord]], Former [[Head of State]]\n|allegiance = {{LBR}}\n| rank = [[Commander]]\n| commands = [[Liberian Army]]\n| battles = *[[First Liberian Civil War]] \n*[[Sierra Leone Civil War]]\n*[[Second Liberian Civil War]] \n}}\n\n'''Charles McArthur Ghankay Taylor''' (born 28 January 1948) is a [[Liberian people|Liberian]] former politician and convicted war criminal who served as the [[President of Liberia#List of Presidents of Liberia|22nd]] [[President of Liberia]] from 2 August 1997 until his resignation on 11 August 2003.<ref name=\"allafricatheend\">{{cite news | first=Ofeibea | last=Quist-Arcton | title=Liberia: Charles Ghankay Taylor, Defiant And Passionate To The End | date=11 August 2003 | publisher=allAfrica.com | url =http://allafrica.com/stories/200308111235.html | accessdate =18 January 2008 }}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=Agencies|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2003/aug/11/westafrica|title=Liberian president Taylor steps down|date=2003-08-11|work=The Guardian|access-date=2020-02-28|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref>\n\nBorn in [[Arthington, Liberia|Arthington]], [[Montserrado County]], [[Liberia]], Taylor earned a degree at [[Bentley College]] in the United States before returning to Liberia to work in the government of [[Samuel Doe]]. After being removed for [[embezzlement]], he eventually arrived in [[Great Socialist People's Libyan Arab Jamahiriya|Libya]], where he was trained as a [[guerrilla fighter]]. He returned to Liberia in 1989 as the head of a Libyan-backed rebel group, the [[National Patriotic Front of Liberia]], to overthrow the Doe government, initiating the [[First Liberian Civil War]] (1989\u201396). Following Doe's execution, Taylor gained control of a large portion of the country and became one of the most prominent [[warlord]]s in Africa.<ref name=\"economistjustice\">{{cite news |url= http://www.economist.com/world/africa/displaystory.cfm?story_id=9262468 |title= Justice at last?|accessdate=5 August 2007|date= 31 May 2007|work=The Economist}}</ref> Following a peace deal that ended the war, Taylor was elected president in the [[1997 Liberian general election|1997 general election]].<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.nytimes.com/2000/12/07/world/in-ruined-liberia-its-despoiler-sits-pretty.html | work=The New York Times | first=Norimitsu | last=Onishi | title=In Ruined Liberia, Its Despoiler Sits Pretty | date=7 December 2000}}</ref>\n\nDuring his term of office, Taylor was accused of [[war crimes]] and [[crimes against humanity]] as a result of his involvement in the [[Sierra Leone Civil War]] (1991\u20132002). Domestically, opposition to his government grew, culminating in the outbreak of the [[Second Liberian Civil War]] (1999\u20132003). By 2003, Taylor had lost control of much of the countryside and was formally indicted by the [[Special Court for Sierra Leone]]. That year, he resigned, as a result of growing international pressure, and went into [[exile]] in [[Nigeria]]. In 2006, the newly elected President, [[Ellen Johnson Sirleaf]], formally requested his extradition. He was detained by UN authorities in Sierra Leone and then at the [[Hague Penitentiary Institution|Penitentiary Institution Haaglanden]] in [[The Hague]], awaiting trial by the Special Court.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.time.com/time/world/article/0,8599,1910365,00.html | work=TIME | title= 'Lies and Rumors': Liberia's Charles Taylor on the Stand| date=14 July 2009 |accessdate=14 July 2009 | first=Leo | last=Cendrowicz}}</ref> He was found guilty in April 2012 of all eleven charges levied by the Special Court, including terror, murder and rape.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-africa-17864387 |work=BBC | title= Taylor Sierra Leone war crimes verdict welcomed | date= 26 April 2012 | accessdate=1 May 2012}}</ref> In May 2012, Taylor was sentenced to 50 years in prison. Reading the sentencing statement, Presiding Judge [[Richard Lussick]] said: \"The accused has been found responsible for aiding and abetting as well as planning some of the most heinous and brutal crimes in recorded human history.\"<ref>{{cite news | url=http://edition.cnn.com/2012/05/30/world/africa/netherlands-taylor-sentencing/index.html |work=CNN | title=Charles Taylor sentenced to 50 years for war crimes | date= 31 May 2012 | accessdate=9 June 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nTaylor was born in [[Arthington, Liberia|Arthington]], a town near the capital of [[Monrovia]], [[Liberia]], on 28 January 1948, to Nelson and Bernice Taylor. He attended [[The Newman School]] in his early years. He took the name \"Ghankay\" later on, possibly to please and gain favor with indigenous Liberians.<ref name='contemporaryreviewreport'>{{cite news|first=Abiodun |last=Onadipe |title=Liberia: Taylor's first year report card. (President Charles Ghankay Taylor) |date=November 1998 |url=http://www.encyclopedia.com/doc/1G1-53450030.html |work=Contemporary Review |accessdate=18 January 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081205164053/http://www.encyclopedia.com/doc/1G1-53450030.html |archivedate=5 December 2008 }}</ref> His mother was a member of the [[Gola (ethnic group)|Gola]] ethnic group, part of the 95% of the people who are indigenous to Liberia. According to most reports, his father was an [[Americo-Liberian]] (a member of Liberia's narrow elite, descended from African-American colonists) who worked as a teacher, sharecropper, lawyer and judge.<ref>{{cite web|last=Burlij|first=Terence|title=A Profile of Charles Taylor|url=https://www.pbs.org/newshour/bb/africa/liberia/taylor-bio.html|work=PBS|publisher=Online NewsHour|accessdate=27 April 2012}}</ref>\n\nIn 1977, Taylor earned a degree at [[Bentley University]] in [[Waltham, Massachusetts]], United States.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.cnn.com/2013/04/26/world/africa/charles-taylor-fast-facts/index.html|title=Charles Taylor Fast Facts|last=Library|first=C. N. N.|website=CNN|access-date=2017-05-22}}</ref>\n\n==Government, imprisonment and escape==\nTaylor supported the [[People's Redemption Council|12 April 1980 coup]] led by [[Samuel Doe]], which resulted in the murder of President [[William R. Tolbert Jr.]] and seizure of power by Doe. Taylor was appointed to the position of Director General of the General Services Agency (GSA), a position that left him in charge of purchasing for the Liberian government. He was sacked in May 1983 for embezzling an estimated $1,000,000 and sending the funds to another bank account.\n\nTaylor fled to the United States but was arrested on 21 May 1984 by two [[United States Marshals Service|US Deputy Marshals]] in [[Somerville, Massachusetts]], on a warrant for extradition to face charges of embezzling $1 million of government funds while the GSA boss.<ref name=star>\"How Charles Taylor Escaped from Jail\". <nowiki>[</nowiki>[[Monrovia]]<nowiki>]</nowiki> ''Daily Star'', 1985-10-05: 10.</ref> Taylor fought extradition with the help of a legal team led by former [[Attorney General of the United States|US Attorney General]] [[Ramsey Clark]].  His lawyers' primary arguments before US District Magistrate Robert J. DeGiacomo stated that his alleged acts of lawbreaking in Liberia were political rather than criminal in nature and that the extradition treaty between the two republics had lapsed. Assistant United States Attorney [[Richard Gaylore Stearns|Richard G. Stearns]] argued that Liberia wished to charge Taylor with theft in office, rather than with political crimes. Stearns' arguments were reinforced by Liberian Justice Minister Jenkins Scott, who flew to the United States to testify at the proceedings.<ref>\"Taylor's Judgement Expected: Final Argument Advanced: Justice Minister Flies Back\". <nowiki>[</nowiki>[[Monrovia]]<nowiki>]</nowiki> ''Sunday Express'' 1984-09-09: 1/8.</ref> Taylor was detained in the [[Plymouth County Correctional Facility]].<ref name=star />\n\nOn 15 September 1985, Taylor and four other inmates escaped from the jail. Two days later, ''[[The Boston Globe]]'' reported that they sawed through a bar covering a window in a dormitory room, after which they lowered themselves {{convert|20|ft}} on knotted sheets and escaped into nearby woods by climbing a fence.<ref name=star />  Shortly thereafter, Taylor and two other escapees were met at nearby Jordan Hospital by Taylor's wife, Enid, and Taylor's sister-in-law, Lucia Holmes Toweh. They drove a getaway car to [[Staten Island]] in New York, where Taylor disappeared. All four of Taylor's fellow escapees, as well as Enid and Toweh, were later apprehended.{{citation needed|date=May 2012}}\n\nIn July 2009, Taylor claimed at his trial that US CIA agents had helped him escape from the maximum security prison in Boston in 1985. This was during his trial by the UN-backed Special Court for Sierra Leone in The Hague. The US Defense Intelligence Agency confirmed that Taylor first started working with US intelligence in the 1980s but refused to give details of his role or US actions, citing national security.<ref>[https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-africa-16627628 Charles Taylor 'worked' for CIA in Liberia], [[BBC]], 2012-01-19.  Accessed 4 June 2012.</ref><ref>[[Bryan Bender]], ''[[The Boston Globe]]'', 17 January 2012, [https://www.bostonglobe.com/metro/2012/01/17/mass-escapee-turned-liberian-dictator-had-spy-agency-ties/DGBhSfjxPVrtoo4WT95bBI/story.html \"Former Liberian dictator Charles Taylor had US spy agency ties\"], ''Boston Globe'', 17 January 2012</ref>\n\n===Civil war===\nTaylor escaped the United States without an issue. He then resurfaced in [[Great Socialist People's Libyan Arab Jamahiriya|Libya]] where he took part in militia training under [[Muammar Gaddafi]], becoming Gaddafi's prot\u00e9g\u00e9.<ref name=\"economistfall\">{{cite news |url= http://www.economist.com/world/international/displaystory.cfm?story_id=9441341 |title= How the mighty are falling | accessdate=17 July 2007 | date= 5 July 2007 |work=The Economist}}</ref> He later left Liberia and traveled to the [[Ivory Coast]], where he founded the [[National Patriotic Front of Liberia]] (NPFL).\n\nIn December 1989, Taylor launched a Gaddafi-funded armed uprising from the Ivory Coast into Liberia to overthrow the Doe regime, leading to the [[First Liberian Civil War]].<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/africa/8429962.stm \"Grim legacy of Liberia's most isolated town\"], ''BBC''</ref> By 1990, his forces controlled most of the country. That same year, [[Prince Johnson]], a senior commander of Taylor's NPFL, broke away and formed the [[Independent National Patriotic Front of Liberia]] (INPFL).\n\nIn September 1990, Johnson captured [[Monrovia]], depriving Taylor of outright victory. Johnson and his forces captured and [[torture]]d Doe to death, instigating a violent political fragmentation of the country.<ref name=MASK>{{cite book|last=Ellis|first=Stephen|title=The Mask of Anarchy: The Destruction of Liberia and the Religious Dimension of African Civil War 1999, 2007 |publisher=Hurst & Company|location=London, UK|isbn=1850654174|pages=1\u201316|year=1999}}</ref> The civil war turned into an [[ethnic conflict]], with seven factions among indigenous peoples and the Americo-Liberians fighting for control of Liberia's resources (especially iron ore, diamonds, timber, and rubber).\n\nAmos Sawyer alleges that Taylor\u2019s aims extended beyond Liberia\u2014that he wanted to re-establish the country as a regional power player.  Taylor's ambitions, held both during the civil war period and into his presidency, resulted not only in domestic  Liberian conflict, but also to regional instability in the form of the [[Sierra Leone Civil War]] and unrest in the forest region of Guinea.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Sawyer|first=Amos|date=2004|title=Violent conflicts and governance challenges in West Africa: the case of the Mano River basin area|url=|journal=Journal of Modern African Studies|volume=42|issue=3|pages=437\u2013463|doi=10.1017/S0022278X04000266}}</ref>\n\nAccording to a 2 June 1999 article in ''[[The Virginian-Pilot]]'',<ref>Sizemore, Bill. [https://groups.google.com/group/misc.activism.progressive/browse_thread/thread/dca03c4012450e0c/f230a667e3ff73d5].  \"Robertson, Liberian Leader Hope to Strike Gold in Coastal Africa\"], ''The Virginian-Pilot''. 2 June 1999.</ref> Taylor had extensive business dealings with American [[televangelist]] [[Pat Robertson]] during the civil war. He gave Robertson the rights to mine for [[diamonds]] in Liberia. According to two [[Operation Blessing]] pilots who reported this incident in 1994 to the Commonwealth of [[Virginia]] for investigation, Robertson used his Operation Blessing aeroplanes to haul diamond-mining equipment to his new mines in Liberia, while telling his ''[[700 Club]]'' viewers that the planes were sending relief supplies to the victims of the [[genocide in Rwanda]]. The subsequent investigation by the Commonwealth of [[Virginia]] concluded that Robertson diverted his ministry's donations to the Liberian diamond-mining operation. [[Attorney General of Virginia]] [[Mark Earley]] blocked any prosecution of Robertson, as the relief supplies were also sent.<ref name='nationrobertson'>{{cite news | first=Max | last=Blumenthal | title= Pat Robertson's Katrina Cash | date=7 September 2005 | url =http://www.thenation.com/doc/20050919/blumenthal | work =The Nation Online | accessdate =19 January 2008 }}</ref>\n\n==Presidency==\nAfter the official end of the civil war in 1996, Taylor ran for president in the [[1997 Liberian general election|1997 general election]]. He campaigned on the notorious slogan \"He killed my ma, he killed my pa, but I will vote for him.\"<ref name='guardianwar'>{{cite news | first=Sarah | last=Left | title=War in Liberia | date=4 August 2003 | url =https://www.theguardian.com/westafrica/story/0,,1008084,00.html |work=The Guardian | accessdate =18 January 2008 | location=London}}</ref>\n\nThe elections were overseen by the United Nations' peacekeeping mission, [[United Nations Observer Mission in Liberia]], along with a contingent from the [[Economic Community of West African States]].<ref name='unomilsite'>{{cite web|url=https://www.un.org/Depts/dpko/dpko/co_mission/unomil.htm |title=UNOMIL |accessdate=18 January 2008 |year=2001 |publisher= Information Technology Section/Department of Public Information }}</ref> Taylor won the election in a landslide, garnering 75 percent of the vote.  Although the election was widely reckoned as free and fair by international observers, Taylor had a huge advantage going into it. He had already taken over the former state radio station and took advantage of its access. Additionally, there was widespread fear in the country that Taylor would resume the war if he lost.\n\nDuring his time in office, Taylor cut the size of the [[Armed Forces of Liberia]], dismissing 2,400\u20132,600 former personnel, many of whom were ethnic [[Krahn]] brought in by former President Doe to give advantage to his people.<ref>Adebayo, ''Liberia's Civil War'', International Peace Academy, 2002, p.235</ref> In its place, Taylor installed the [[Anti-Terrorist Unit (Liberia)|Anti-Terrorist Unit]], the Special Operations Division of the [[Law enforcement in Liberia|Liberian National Police]] (LNP), which he used as his own private army.\n\nDuring his presidency, Taylor was alleged to have been involved directly in the [[Sierra Leone Civil War]]. He was accused of aiding the rebel [[Revolutionary United Front]] (RUF) through weapon sales in exchange for [[blood diamond]]s. Due to a UN embargo against arms sales to Liberia at the time, these weapons were largely purchased on the [[black market]] through arms smugglers such as [[Viktor Bout]].<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/asia/merchant-of-death-who-armed-tyrants-fights-extradition-to-us-1208489.html | title='Merchant of Death' who armed tyrants fights extradition to US | date=23 December 2008 |work=The Independent   | location=London | first=Andy | last=McSmith}}</ref> Taylor was charged with aiding and abetting RUF atrocities against civilians, which left many thousands dead or mutilated, with unknown numbers of people abducted and tortured. He was also accused of assisting the RUF in the recruitment of [[child soldiers]]. In addition to aiding the RUF in these acts, Taylor reportedly personally directed RUF operations in Sierra Leone.<ref>''Merchant of Death: Money, Guns, Planes, and the Man Who Makes War Possible''. Douglas Farah, Stephen Braun. p. 167</ref>\n\nTaylor obtained spiritual and other advice from the evangelist [[K.A. Paul|Kilari Anand Paul]].<ref name='newyorkerpersuader'>{{cite news | first=William | last=Finnegan | title=The Persuader | date= 1 September 2003 | url =https://www.newyorker.com/archive/2003/09/01/030901ta_talk_finnegan?printable=true | work =The New Yorker | accessdate =19 January 2008}}</ref> As president, he was known for his flamboyant style.<ref name=Preacher/> Upon being charged by the UN of being a gunrunner and diamond smuggler during his presidency, Taylor appeared in all-white robes and begged God for forgiveness, while denying the charges.<ref name=Preacher>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/africa/2963086.stm|title=Charles Taylor \u2013 preacher, warlord, president|newspaper=BBC News|date=13 July 2009}}</ref> He was reported to have said that \"Jesus Christ was accused of being a murderer in his time.\"<ref name=Preacher/>\n\n===Rebellion and indictment===\nIn 1999, a rebellion against Taylor began in northern Liberia, led by a group calling itself [[Liberians United for Reconciliation and Democracy]] (LURD). This group was frequently accused of atrocities, and is thought to have been backed by the government of neighboring [[Guinea]].<ref name='humanrightswatchlurd'>{{cite journal|title=Back to the Brink|journal=Human Rights Watch Report|date=1 May 2002|volume=14|issue=A |url=https://www.hrw.org/reports/2002/liberia/|accessdate=18 January 2008}}</ref> This uprising signaled the beginning of the [[Second Liberian Civil War]].\n\nBy early 2003, LURD had gained control of northern Liberia. That year, a second [[Ivory Coast|Ivorian]]-backed rebel group, [[Movement for Democracy in Liberia]] (MODEL), emerged in southern Liberia and achieved rapid successes.<ref name='humanrightswatchmodel'>{{cite news | title=Liberia |date=January 2004 | url =https://www.hrw.org/english/docs/2004/01/29/liberi7246.htm | work =Briefing to the 60th Session of the UN Commission on Human Rights | accessdate =18 January 2008 }}</ref> By the summer, Taylor's government controlled only about a third of Liberia: Monrovia and the central part of the country. More than one-third of the total population lived in this area.\n\nOn 7 March 2003, the [[Special Court for Sierra Leone]] (SCSL) issued a [[sealed indictment]] for Taylor.<ref>[http://www.sc-sl.org/CASES/ProsecutorvsCharlesTaylor/tabid/107/Default.aspx \"The Prosecutor vs. Charles Ghankay Taylor\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120604005902/http://www.sc-sl.org/CASES/ProsecutorvsCharlesTaylor/tabid/107/Default.aspx |date=4 June 2012 }}, The Special Court for Sierra Leone. Retrieved 26 March 2010</ref>  Earlier that year, Liberian forces had killed [[Sam Bockarie]], a leading member of the RUF in Sierra Leone, in a shootout under Taylor's orders. Some have claimed that Taylor ordered Bockarie killed in order to prevent the leader from testifying against him at the SCSL.<ref name='perspective'>{{cite news | title=The Mysterious Death of a Fugitive | date=7 May 2003 | work=The Perspective |location=Atlanta, Georgia, United States | url =http://www.theperspective.org/fugitivebockarie.html | accessdate =18 January 2008 }}</ref>\n\nIn June 2003, Alan White, the Prosecutor to the Special Court unsealed the indictment and announced publicly that Taylor was charged with war crimes. The indictment asserted that Taylor created and backed the RUF rebels in Sierra Leone, who were accused of a range of atrocities, including the use of [[child soldier]]s.<ref name='taylorindictment'>{{Cite book| first=David M. | last=Crane| contribution=CASE NO. SCSL \u2013 03 \u2013 I| title=The Special Court for Sierra Leone| editor-first=| editor-last=| publisher=United Nations and the Government of Sierra Leone| place=Freetown, Sierra Leone| date=3 March 2003| id= | contribution-url=http://www.sc-sl.org/Documents/SCSC-03-01-I-001.html | accessdate=18 January 2008 }}</ref><ref name=\"Female Victim\">{{cite web|url=https://www.liberianobserver.com/news/victim-pleads-for-war-crimes-court/ |title=Female Victim Pleads for War Crimes Court |author= Joaquin M. Sendolo |work=[[Liberian Observer]] |date=21 March 2018 |accessdate=21 June 2018 }}</ref> The Prosecutor also said that Taylor's administration had harbored members of [[Al-Qaeda]] sought in connection with the 1998 bombings of U.S. embassies in [[Kenya]] and [[Tanzania]].<ref>{{cite news| url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/africa/4577547.stm|publisher=BBC| date=24 May 2005 | title=UN pressed over Liberia's Taylor| author=Susannah Price | accessdate=2 January 2010}}</ref>\n\nThe indictment was unsealed during Taylor's official visit to [[Ghana]], where he was participating in peace talks with MODEL and LURD officials. As result, the possibility arose that Taylor might be arrested by Ghanaian authorities; in response, Taylor's chief bodyguard and military commander [[Benjamin Yeaten]] threatened to execute Ghanians who lived in Liberia, deterring Ghana's government from taking action.<ref name=\"Female Victim\"/> With the backing of South African president [[Thabo Mbeki]] and against the urging of [[Sierra Leone]] president [[Ahmad Tejan Kabbah]], Ghana consequently declined to detain Taylor, who returned to Monrovia.\n\n===Resignation===\nDuring Taylor's absence for the peace talks in Ghana, the U.S. government was alleged to have urged [[Vice President of Liberia|Vice President]] [[Moses Blah]] to seize power.<ref name='bbcblahprofile'>{{cite news | first=Jonathan | last=Paye-Layleh | title=Profile: Moses Blah | date=10 August 2003 | url =http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/world/africa/3140063.stm |work=BBC News | accessdate =18 January 2008 }}</ref> Upon his return, Taylor briefly dismissed Blah from his post, only to reinstate him a few days later.\n\nIn July 2003, LURD initiated a siege of Monrovia, and several bloody battles were fought as Taylor's forces halted rebel attempts to capture the city. The pressure on Taylor increased as U.S. President [[George W. Bush]] twice that month stated that Taylor \"must leave Liberia\". On 9 July, Nigerian President [[Olusegun Obasanjo]] offered Taylor [[exile]] in his country on the condition that Taylor stay out of Liberian politics.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.cnn.com/2003/WORLD/africa/07/09/liberia/ | title=Nigeria would shield Taylor from trial|publisher=CNN|date=10 July 2003 | accessdate=28 April 2010}}</ref>\n\nTaylor insisted that he would resign only if U.S. [[peacekeeping]] troops were deployed to Liberia. Bush publicly called upon Taylor to resign and leave the country in order for any American involvement to be considered. Meanwhile, several African states, in particular the [[Economic Community of West African States]] (ECOWAS) under the leadership of Nigeria, sent troops under the banner of [[ECOMIL]] to Liberia.<ref name=\"nytimesnigeria\">{{cite news | first=Felicity | last=Barringer | title= Nigeria Readies Peace Force for Liberia; Battles Go On | date=24 July 2003 | url =https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9C0CE5D6153FF937A15754C0A9659C8B63 | work =The New York Times | accessdate =18 January 2008 }}</ref>\n\nLogistical support was provided by a California company called [[Pacific Architects & Engineers|PAE]] Government Services Inc., which was given a $10 million contract by the [[U.S. State Department]].<ref name=\"nytimesnigeria\" /> On 6 August, a 32-member U.S. military assessment team were deployed as a liaison with the ECOWAS troops,<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.cnn.com/2003/WORLD/africa/07/07/liberia/ | title=Liberia's Taylor not ready to leave| date=7 July 2003|publisher=CNN | accessdate=28 April 2010}}</ref> landing from the 26th [[Marine Expeditionary Unit]], commanded by Colonel A.P. Frick, from three U.S. Navy amphibious ships waiting off the Liberian coast.\n\nOn 10 August, Taylor appeared on national television to announce that he would resign the following day and hand power to Vice President Blah. He harshly criticized the United States in his [[farewell address]], saying that the [[Presidency of George W. Bush|Bush administration]]'s insistence that he leave the country would hurt Liberia.<ref name=\"allafricatheend\" /> On 11 August, Taylor resigned, with Blah serving as president until a transitional government was established on 14 October. [[Ghana]]ian President [[John Kufuor]], South African President [[Thabo Mbeki]], and [[Mozambique|Mozambican]] President [[Joaquim Chissano]], all representing African regional councils, were present at his announcement. The U.S. brought [[Joint Task Force Liberia]]'s [[Amphibious Ready Group]] of three warships with 2,300 [[United States Marine Corps|Marines]] into view of the coast. Taylor flew to Nigeria, where the Nigerian government provided houses for him and his entourage in [[Calabar]].\n\n==Exile==\nIn November 2003, the [[United States Congress]] passed a bill that included a reward offer of two million dollars for Taylor's capture. While the peace agreement had guaranteed Taylor safe exile in Nigeria, it also required that he refrain from influencing Liberian politics. His critics said he disregarded this prohibition.  On 4 December, [[Interpol]] issued a [[red notice]] regarding Taylor, suggesting that countries had a duty to arrest him. Taylor was placed on Interpol's [[Most Wanted list]], declaring him wanted for [[crimes against humanity]] and breaches of the 1949 [[Fourth Geneva Convention|Geneva Convention]], and noting that he should be considered dangerous. Nigeria stated it would not submit to Interpol's demands, agreeing to deliver Taylor to Liberia only in the event that the President of Liberia requested his return.\n\nOn 17 March 2006, [[Ellen Johnson Sirleaf]], the newly elected President of Liberia, submitted an official request to Nigeria for Taylor's [[extradition]]. This request was granted on 25 March, whereby Nigeria agreed to release Taylor to stand trial in the [[Special Court for Sierra Leone]] (SCSL). Nigeria agreed only to release Taylor and not to extradite him, as no [[extradition treaty]] existed between the two countries.\n\n===Disappearance and arrest===\nThree days after Nigeria announced its intent to transfer Taylor to Liberia, the leader disappeared from the seaside villa where he had been living in exile.<ref>{{cite news| author=Polgreen, Lydia| title=Nigeria Says Ex-President of Liberia Has Disappeared| journal=The New York Times| date=29 March 2006| url=https://nytimes.com/2006/03/29/international/africa/29liberia.html}}</ref> A week before that, Nigerian authorities had taken the unusual step of allowing local press to accompany census takers into Taylor\u2019s Calabar compound.\n\nNigerian President [[Olusegun Obasanjo]] was scheduled to meet with President Bush less than 48 hours after Taylor was reported missing. Speculation ensued that Bush would refuse to meet with Obasanjo if Taylor were not apprehended. Less than 12 hours prior to the scheduled meeting between the two heads of state, Taylor was reported apprehended en route to Liberia.\n\nOn 29 March, Taylor tried to cross the border into [[Cameroon]] through the border town of Gamboru in northeastern Nigeria. His [[Range Rover]] with Nigerian diplomatic plates was stopped by border guards, and Taylor's identity was eventually established. [[United States Department of State|US State Department]] staff later reported that significant amounts of cash and heroin were found in the vehicle.\n\nUpon his arrival at [[Roberts International Airport]] in [[Harbel]], Liberia, Taylor was arrested and handcuffed by LNP officers, who immediately transferred responsibility for the custody of Taylor to the [[United Nations Mission in Liberia]] (UNMIL). Irish UNMIL soldiers escorted Taylor aboard a UN helicopter to [[Freetown]], Sierra Leone, where he was delivered to the SCSL.\n\n==Trial==\n[[File:Monrovia news board 2008.jpeg|thumb|Newsboard documenting the Charles Taylor case]]\nThe SCSL prosecutor originally indicted Taylor on 3 March 2003 on a 17-counts for [[war crimes]] and crimes against humanity committed during the conflict in Sierra Leone. On 16 March 2006, a SCSL judge gave leave to amend the indictment against Taylor. Under the amended indictment, Taylor was charged with 11 counts. At Taylor's initial appearance before the court on 3 April 2006, he entered a plea of not guilty.<ref name='spslIndictment'>{{cite news | first= Desmond, QC, Chief Prosecutor, Special Court for Sierra Leone | last=de Silva | title=Chief Prosecutor Announces the Arrival of Charles Taylor at the Special Court | date=29 March 2006 | url =http://www.sc-sl.org/Press/prosecutor-032906.pdf | work =Press Release from the Special Court for Sierra Leone | accessdate =19 January 2008 |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20071201194256/http://www.sc-sl.org/Press/prosecutor-032906.pdf <!-- Bot retrieved archive --> |archivedate = 1 December 2007}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=THE PROSECUTOR OF THE SPECIAL COURT V. CHARLES GHANKAY TAYLOR Monday, 4 June 2007|url=http://www.sc-sl.org/LinkClick.aspx?fileticket=SA/7CCB4VCc=&tabid=160|publisher=Special Court of Sierra Leone|accessdate=6 December 2013|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130521023914/http://www.sc-sl.org/LinkClick.aspx?fileticket=SA%2F7CCB4VCc%3D&tabid=160|archivedate=21 May 2013|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nIn early June 2006, the decision on whether to hold Taylor's trial in Freetown or in [[Leidschendam]] had not yet been made by the new SCSL president, [[George Gelaga King]]. King's predecessor had pushed for the trial to be held abroad because of fear that a local trial would be politically destabilizing in an area where Taylor still had influence.<ref name=\"economistjustice\"/>  The Appeals Chamber of the Special Court dismissed a motion by Taylor's defence team, who argued that their client could not get a fair trial there and also wanted the Special Court to withdraw the request to move the trial to Leidschendam.<ref name='newafricantrial'>{{cite news | title =Will Taylor Get a Fair Trial? | date =February 2007 | url =http://www.fortaylor.net/article17.htm | work =New African (Sierra Leone) | accessdate =19 January 2008 | url-status =dead | archiveurl =https://web.archive.org/web/20071026003901/http://www.fortaylor.net/article17.htm | archivedate =26 October 2007 | df =dmy-all }}</ref><ref name=\"IRIN where\">{{cite news | title=SIERRA LEONE: Decision on Taylor trial venue rests with head of Special Court | date=19 January 2008 | publisher=Irin News | url =http://www.irinnews.org/report.aspx?reportid=59190 | work =New African (Sierra Leone) | accessdate =19 January 2008 }}</ref>\n\nOn 15 June 2006, the [[British government]] agreed to jail Taylor in the United Kingdom in the event that he was convicted by the SCSL. This fulfilled a condition laid down by the [[Dutch government]], which had stated it was willing to host the trial but would not jail him if convicted. British Foreign Minister [[Margaret Beckett]] stated that new legislation would be required to accommodate this arrangement.<ref name='bbcagrees'>{{cite news | title=UK Agrees to Jail Charles Taylor | date=15 June 2006 | url =http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/world/africa/5082664.stm |work=BBC News | accessdate =19 January 2008 }}</ref> This legislation came in the form of the International Tribunals (Sierra Leone) Act 2007. <ref>http://www.legislation.gov.uk/ukpga/2007/7/enacted</ref> While awaiting his extradition to the [[Netherlands]], Taylor was held in a UN jail in Freetown.<ref name='CBCjail'>{{cite news | title=Charles Taylor jailed in Sierra Leone | date=29 March 2006 | url =https://www.cbc.ca/news/world/charles-taylor-jailed-in-sierra-leone-1.589212 | work =CBC News | accessdate =19 January 2008 }}</ref>\n\nOn 16 June 2006, the [[UNSC|United Nations Security Council]] agreed unanimously to allow Taylor to be sent to Leidschendam for trial; on 20 June 2006, Taylor was extradited and flown to [[Rotterdam Airport]] in the Netherlands. He was taken into custody and held in the detention centre of the [[International Criminal Court]], located in the [[Scheveningen]] section of The Hague.<ref name='forum'>{{cite news|first=Lansana |last=Fofana |title=Mixed Feelings over Charles Taylor's Transfer to The Hague |date=20 June 2006 |url=http://globalpolicy.igc.org/intljustice/wanted/2006/0620mixedfeelings.htm |work=Global Policy Forum |accessdate=19 January 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090107175200/http://globalpolicy.igc.org/intljustice/wanted/2006/0620mixedfeelings.htm |archivedate=7 January 2009 }}</ref> The Association for the Legal Defence of Charles G. Taylor was established in June 2006 to assist in his legal defence.\n\nWhen Taylor's trial opened on 4 June 2007, Taylor boycotted the proceeding and was not present. Through a letter that was read by his attorney to the court, he justified his absence by alleging that at that moment he was not ensured a fair and impartial trial.<ref>{{cite news | last = Hudson | first = Alexandra  | title = Taylor absent as trial gets underway |work=IOL| date = 4 June 2007 | url = http://www.int.iol.co.za/index.php?set_id=1&click_id=86&art_id=nw20070604110955292C367300\n| accessdate =4 June 2007}}</ref>\n\nOn 20 August 2007, Taylor's defence, now led by [[Courtenay Griffiths]], obtained a postponement of the trial until 7 January 2008.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/africa/6954627.stm |title=Taylor trial delayed until 2008 |accessdate=20 August 2007 |work=BBC News  | date=20 August 2007}}</ref> During the trial, the chief prosecutor alleged that a key insider witness who testified against Taylor went into hiding after being threatened for giving evidence against Taylor.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://edition.cnn.com/2008/WORLD/africa/02/28/Taylor.warcrimes.ap/index.html |title=Witness in Taylor war crimes trial in hiding after threats |accessdate=28 February 2008 |work=CNN |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20080229224224/http://edition.cnn.com/2008/WORLD/africa/02/28/Taylor.warcrimes.ap/index.html <!-- Bot retrieved archive --> |archivedate = 29 February 2008}}</ref> Furthermore, Joseph \"Zigzag\" Marzah, a former military commander, testified that Charles Taylor celebrated his new-found status during the civil war by ordering human sacrifice, including the killings of Taylor's opponents and allies that were perceived to have betrayed Taylor, and by having a pregnant woman buried alive in sand.<ref>\"[http://www.aljazeera.com/news/africa/2008/03/200852512151608819.html \"Shock testimony at Taylor trial\"]. ''[[Al Jazeera]]''.</ref> Marzah also accused Taylor of forcing [[cannibalism]] on his soldiers in order to terrorize their enemies.<ref>\"[http://www.cnn.com/2008/WORLD/africa/03/13/warcrimes.taylor.ap/index.html Top aide testifies Taylor ordered soldiers to eat victims].\" ''[[CNN]]''.</ref>\n\nIn January 2009, the prosecution finished presenting its evidence against Taylor and closed its case on 27 February 2009. On 4 May 2009, a defence motion for a judgment on acquittal was dismissed, and arguments for Taylor's defence began in July 2009.<ref>Winter, Renate. \"Foreword,\" [http://www.sc-sl.org/LinkClick.aspx?fileticket=%2fuI3lqaO5D0%3d&tabid=53 ''Sixth Annual Report of the President of the Special Court for Sierra Leone: June 2008 to May 2009''] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120227083926/http://www.sc-sl.org/LinkClick.aspx?fileticket=%2FuI3lqaO5D0%3D&tabid=53 |date=27 February 2012 }}. Retrieved 11 January 2010.</ref> Taylor testified in his own defence from July through November 2009.<ref>[[Associated Press]]. [https://www.nytimes.com/aponline/2010/01/11/world/AP-EU-War-Crimes-Taylor.html \"Taylor: I Didn't Know Sierra Leone Rebel Pre-1991\"], ''The New York Times'', 11 January 2010. Retrieved 11 January 2010.</ref> The defence rested its case on 12 November 2010, with closing arguments set for early February 2011.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://edition.cnn.com/2010/WORLD/africa/11/12/liberia.taylor.trial/?hpt=T2|title=Charles Taylor's team rests case in war crimes trial|accessdate=14 November 2010|date=12 November 2010|work=CNN}}</ref>\n\nOn 8 February 2011, the trial court ruled in a 2\u20131 decision that it would not accept Taylor's trial summary, as the summary had not been submitted by the 14 January deadline. In response, Taylor and his counsel boycotted the trial and refused an order by the court to begin closing arguments. This boycott came soon after the [[United States diplomatic cables leak|2010 leak of American diplomatic cables]] by [[WikiLeaks]], in which the United States discussed the possibility of extraditing Taylor for prosecution in the United States in the event of his acquittal by the SCSL. Taylor's counsel cited the leaked cable and the court's decision as evidence of an international conspiracy against Taylor.<ref>{{cite news|last=Corder|first=Mike|title=Charles Taylor Boycotts End of War Crimes Trial|url=http://www.nbcnews.com/id/41478144|agency=Associated Press|newspaper=MSNBC|date=8 February 2011|accessdate=26 March 2012}}</ref>\n\nOn 3 March, the appeals court of the SCSL overturned the trial court's decision, ruling that as the trial court had not established that Taylor had been counseled by the court and personally indicated his intent to waive his right to a trial summary, Taylor's [[due process]] rights would be violated by preventing him from submitting a trial summary. The appeals court ordered the trial court to accept the summary and set a date for the beginning of closing arguments.<ref>{{cite news|title=Judges allow Charles Taylor's closing arguments|url=https://www.google.com/hostednews/afp/article/ALeqM5hLGZ8fiXA0-Ni7zTLGVHFF8fSNOA?docId=CNG.5eda08e8eb1b42b79c577796fd7c8cba.9d1|agency=AFP|newspaper=Google News|date=3 March 2011|accessdate=4 March 2011}}</ref>  On 11 March, the closing arguments ended and it was announced that the court would begin the process to reach a verdict.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://english.aljazeera.net/news/europe/2011/03/2011311172946791811.html |title=Trial of Charles Taylor ends \u2013 Europe |publisher=Al Jazeera English |date= |accessdate=8 June 2013}}</ref>\n\n===Verdict===\nThe verdict was announced in Leidschendam on 26 April 2012.<ref>{{cite news | url= http://www.time.com/time/world/article/0,8599,2113215,00.html| work=TIME | title= Warlord Convicted: Liberia's Charles Taylor Found Guilty of War Crimes| date=26 April 2012| first=Leo| last=Cendrowicz}}</ref> The SCSL unanimously ruled that he was guilty of all 11 counts of \"aiding and abetting\" war crimes and crimes against humanity,<ref name=BBC305>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-africa-18259596 |title=Liberia ex-leader Charles Taylor get 50 years in jail |date=30 May 2012 |work=BBC News |accessdate=30 May 2012}}</ref> making him the first (former) head of state to be convicted by an international tribunal since [[Karl D\u00f6nitz]] at the [[Nuremberg Trials]]. Taylor was convicted of the following 11 charges:<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-africa-12391507 |title=The charges against Charles Taylor |date=8 February 2012 |work=BBC News |accessdate=30 May 2012}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Count\n! Crime\n! Type*\n! Ruling\n|-\n| colspan=\"4\"  style=\"text-align:center; background:#00d0d0;\"|Terrorising the civilian population and collective punishments\n|-\n| | 1\n| | Acts of terrorism\n| |WC\n|| Guilty\n|-\n| colspan=\"4\"  style=\"text-align:center; background:#00d0d0;\"|Unlawful killings\n|-\n||2\n||Murder\n||CAH\n||Guilty\n|-\n||3\n||Violence to life, health and physical or mental well-being of persons, in particular murder\n||WC\n||Guilty\n|-\n| colspan=\"4\"  style=\"text-align:center; background:#00d0d0;\"|Sexual violence\n|-\n||4\n||Rape\n||CAH\n||Guilty\n|-\n||5\n||Sexual slavery and any other form of sexual violence\n||CAH\n||Guilty\n|-\n||6\n|| Outrages upon personal dignity\n||WC\n||Guilty\n|-\n| colspan=\"4\"  style=\"text-align:center; background:#00d0d0;\"|Physical violence\n|-\n||7\n||Violence to life, health and physical or mental well-being of persons, in particular cruel treatment\n||WC\n||Guilty\n|-\n||8\n||Other inhumane acts\n||CAH\n||Guilty\n|-\n| colspan=\"4\"  style=\"text-align:center; background:#00d0d0;\"|Use of child soldiers\n|-\n||9\n||Conscripting or enlisting children under the age of 15 years into armed forces or groups, or using them to participate actively in hostilities\n||VIHL\n||Guilty\n|-\n| colspan=\"4\"  style=\"text-align:center; background:#00d0d0;\"|Abductions and forced labor\n|-\n||10\n||Enslavement\n||CAH\n||Guilty\n|-\n| colspan=\"4\"  style=\"text-align:center; background:#00d0d0;\"|Looting\n|-\n||11\n||[[Pillage]]\n||WC\n||Guilty\n|-\n| Colspan=4 | *Explanation of type of crime: {{plainlist|\n* CAH {{=}} [[Crimes against humanity]]\n* WC {{=}} Violation of Article 3 common to the Geneva Conventions and of Additional Protocol II (war crimes)\n* VIHL {{=}} Other serious violation of international humanitarian law}}\n|}\n\nAt his trial, Taylor claimed that he was a victim, denied the charges and compared his actions of torture and crimes against humanity to the actions of [[George W. Bush]] in the [[War on Terror]].<ref>{{cite news| url= http://articles.cnn.com/2012-05-16/africa/world_africa_netherlands-taylor-sentencing_1_war-crimes-liberian-president-charles-taylor-international-tribunal?_s=PM:AFRICA| work= CNN| title= In his last stand, Charles Taylor defends himself as a peacemaker| date= 16 May 2012| access-date= 21 May 2012| archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20120520235156/http://articles.cnn.com/2012-05-16/africa/world_africa_netherlands-taylor-sentencing_1_war-crimes-liberian-president-charles-taylor-international-tribunal?_s=PM:AFRICA| archive-date= 20 May 2012| url-status= dead| df= dmy-all}}</ref> Sentencing hearings commenced on 3 May<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cnbc.com/id/47286835/Prosecutors_seek_80_year_sentence_for_Charles_Taylor|title=Prosecutors seek 80-year sentence for Charles Taylor|date=3 May 2012|publisher=CNBC|accessdate=30 May 2012}}{{Dead link|date=November 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> and were announced on 30 May. Taylor was sentenced to 50 years in prison.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/news/world/ex-liberian-president-charles-taylor-sentenced-to-50-years-in-prison/article2447255/ |title=Globe & Mail article |location=Toronto |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120530103119/http://www.theglobeandmail.com/news/world/ex-liberian-president-charles-taylor-sentenced-to-50-years-in-prison/article2447255/ |archivedate=30 May 2012 }}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2012/may/30/charles-taylor-sentenced-50-years-war-crimes|title=Charles Taylor sentenced to 50 years in prison for war crimes|last=Bowcott|first=Owen|date=2012-05-30|work=The Guardian|access-date=2019-12-03|last2=agencies|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref> He was about 64 at the time. His sentence was upheld on appeal.<ref>[http://www.aljazeera.com/news/africa/2013/09/charles-taylor-appeal-verdict-due-20139266564497970.html \"Judges uphold Charles Taylor's jail sentence\"], Al Jazeera, 26 September 2013.</ref>\n\nSierra Leone's government described the sentence as \"a step forward as justice has been done, though the magnitude of the sentence is not commensurate with the atrocities committed\".<ref name=BBC305 />\n\nTaylor appealed against the verdict, but on 26 September 2013 Appeals Chamber of the Special Court confirmed his guilt and the penalty of 50 years in prison. On 15 October 2013 he was transferred to British custody, and began serving his sentence at [[HM Prison Frankland]] in County Durham, England.<ref>{{cite news|title=Ex-warlord Charles Taylor's family say he is being 'ill-treated' in British jail|newspaper=[[Telegraph Media Group|The Telegraph]]|location=[[London]]|date=2013-10-29|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/africaandindianocean/liberia/10412158/Ex-warlord-Charles-Taylors-family-say-he-is-being-ill-treated-in-British-jail.html|accessdate=2014-04-11}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Liberia's Charles Taylor transferred to UK|newspaper=[[BBC News]]|publisher=[[BBC]]|date=2013-10-15|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-africa-24537834|accessdate=2014-04-11}}</ref> Taylor's attorneys filed a motion to have him transferred to a prison in Rwanda,<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2013/09/27/world/africa/charles-taylor-sierra-leone-war-crimes-case.html?_r=0|title=50-Year Sentence Upheld for Ex-President of Liberia|date=26 September 2013| newspaper=The New York Times|accessdate=29 September 2013|first1=Marlise|last1=Simons|first2=Alan|last2=Cowell}}</ref> but in March 2015 the motion was denied and he was ordered to continue serving his sentence in the United Kingdom.<ref>[https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-32055482 \"Ex-Liberia President Charles Taylor to stay in UK prison\"] ''BBC News'', March 25, 2015. Retrieved December 30, 2015.</ref> In 2017 it was found that he had been making phone calls from the prison to provide guidance to the National Patriotic Party and threaten some of his enemies.<ref name=phone>{{cite magazine |date=24 February 2017 |title=Phone a Fiend |magazine=Private eye |publisher=Pressdram Ltd |issue=1438 |page=18  }}</ref>\n\n==Family==\nIn 1997 Taylor married [[Jewel Taylor]], with whom he has one son. She filed for divorce in 2005, citing her husband's exile in Nigeria and the difficulty of visiting him due to a UN travel ban on her.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.irinnews.org/report.aspx?reportid=57741|title=LIBERIA: Charles Taylor's wife has divorce petition granted|accessdate=31 July 2010|work=IRIN Africa|date=6 January 2006}}</ref> The divorce was granted in 2006. Jewel Taylor currently serves as the [[Vice President of Liberia]].\n\nPhillip Taylor, Taylor's son with Jewel, remained in Liberia following his father's extradition to the SCSL. He was arrested by Liberian police officials on 5 March 2011 and charged with attempted murder in connection with an assault on the son of an immigration officer who had assisted in Charles Taylor's extradition;<ref name=likefather>{{cite news|first=Edwin G.|last=Genoway|url=http://www.thenewdawnliberia.com/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=2891:like-father-like-sons&catid=25:politics&Itemid=59|title=Like Father, Like Sons|newspaper=The New Dawn|date=7 March 2011|accessdate=7 March 2011}}</ref> the mother of the victim claimed that Phillip Taylor had sworn vengeance against the immigration officer.  He was arrested at [[Buchanan, Liberia|Buchanan]] in [[Grand Bassa County]],<ref>{{cite news|last=Toe|first=Jerome W.|title=Charles Taylor's Son Arrested: For Attempted Murder|work=[[Liberian Observer|Daily Observer]]|date=7 March 2011|pages=1, 26}}</ref> allegedly while attempting to cross the border into the Ivory Coast.<ref name=likefather />\n\nTaylor has three children with his second wife Victoria Addison Taylor; the youngest, Charlize, was born in March 2010.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.csmonitor.com/World/Africa/2012/0425/In-Monrovia-Charles-Taylor-s-wife-awaits-his-verdict|first=Kate|last=Thomas|title=In Monrovia, Charles Taylor's wife awaits his verdict|work=Christian Science Monitor|date=25 April 2012|accessdate=25 July 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/africa/8564395.stm|title=Wife of war crimes suspect Charles Taylor gives birth|work=BBC News|date=12 March 2010|accessdate=25 July 2015}}</ref> In 2014, Victoria was denied a visa to visit her husband while he serves his sentence in the United Kingdom.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.gnnliberia.com/articles/2014/01/29/charles-taylor%E2%80%99s-wife-denied-visa-husband-celebrates-66th-birth-anniversary|title=Charles Taylor's Wife Denied Visa, As Husband Celebrates 66th Birth Anniversary behind Bars in UK|work=GNN Liberia|date=29 January 2014|accessdate=25 July 2015|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150725220343/http://www.gnnliberia.com/articles/2014/01/29/charles-taylor%E2%80%99s-wife-denied-visa-husband-celebrates-66th-birth-anniversary|archivedate=25 July 2015|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://frontpageafricaonline.com/index.php/news/899-no-access-to-family-taylor-s-wife-laments-after-uk-denies-visa|title=No access to family: Taylor's wife laments after UK denies visa|work=Front Page Africa|date=5 March 2014|accessdate=25 July 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150726003821/http://frontpageafricaonline.com/index.php/news/899-no-access-to-family-taylor-s-wife-laments-after-uk-denies-visa|archive-date=26 July 2015|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nTaylor also has another son, a U.S. citizen named [[Charles McArther Emmanuel]], born to his college girlfriend. Emmanuel was arrested in 2006 after entering the United States and was charged with three counts, including participation in torture while serving in the Anti-Terrorist Unit in Liberia during his father's presidency. The law that prosecuted Taylor was put in place in 1994, before \"extraordinary rendition\" in an attempt to prevent U.S. citizens from committing acts of torture overseas. To date, this is the only prosecuted case.<ref>\"[http://www.cnn.com/2008/CRIME/09/30/taylor.torture.trial.ap/index.html?iref=mpstoryview Ex-prisoner: Taylor's son laughed at torture\"] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081218050420/http://www.cnn.com/2008/CRIME/09/30/taylor.torture.trial.ap/index.html?iref=mpstoryview |date=18 December 2008 }}, ''[[CNN]]'', 30 September 2008.</ref> In October 2008, Emmanuel was convicted on all three counts and sentenced to 97 years in prison.<ref>Couwels, John. \"[http://www.cnn.com/2008/CRIME/10/30/taylor.torture.verdict/index.html Ex-Liberian president's son convicted of torture\"], ''[[CNN]]''. 30 October 2008.</ref>\n\n==In popular culture==\n* Taylor is a prominent character in the 2004 novel [[The Darling (novel)|''The Darling'']] by Russell Banks.\n* The character Andre Baptiste Sr. from the 2005 film ''[[Lord of War]]'' is partially based on Taylor.<ref>{{cite journal|journal=The Boston Globe|date=16 September 2005|first=Ty|last=Burr|title=Provocative 'War' Skillfully Takes Aim|pages=D1}}</ref>\n* Taylor appears in the 2008 documentary ''[[Pray the Devil Back to Hell]]''.\n\n==See also==\n\n* [[Exotic Tropic Timber Enterprises]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* {{Cite book |title=The Liberian Civil War |first=Mark |last=Huband |year=1998 |location=London |publisher=F. Cass |isbn=0-7146-4340-8 |url-access=registration |url=https://archive.org/details/isbn_9780714647852 }}\n* {{Cite book |title=Charles Taylor and Liberia: Ambition and Atrocity in Africa's Lone Star State |first=Colin |last=Waugh |year=2011 |location=London |publisher=Zed Books Ltd |isbn=978-184813-847-6 }}\n\n==External links==\n* Trial proceedings are available directly from: [https://web.archive.org/web/20080501184018/http://www.sc-sl.org/ the UN Special Court for Sierra Leone]''\n* [http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/africa/2963086.stm BBC profile of Charles Taylor]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20060322014022/http://jurist.law.pitt.edu/currentawareness/taylor.php Charles Taylor legal news and resources], [[JURIST]]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20060418014254/http://jurist.law.pitt.edu/forumy/2006/03/handing-over-charles-taylor-its-time.php Handing Over Charles Taylor: It's Time], [[JURIST]] (op-ed by David Crane, former Chief Prosecutor for the Special Court for Sierra Leone who signed the indictment for Charles Taylor)\n* [http://www.cnn.com/2006/WORLD/africa/03/25/taylor.liberia/index.html Nigeria agrees to hand Taylor over to Liberia]\n* [http://edition.cnn.com/2006/WORLD/africa/03/29/taylor.profile/index.html \"Charles Taylor: A wanted man\"], CNN, 29 March 2006.\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20080501184018/http://www.sc-sl.org/ Special Court for Sierra Leone]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20051115090137/http://www.trial-ch.org/trialwatch/profiles/en/facts/p98.html The trial of Charles Taylor \u2013 TRIAL WATCH]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20060510044646/http://www.usip.org/events/2006/0407_taylor.html Charles Taylor on Trial] [[U.S. Institute of Peace]], 7 April 2006 (Audio)\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20090723081243/http://www.theyoungturks.com/story/2009/7/16/650/03802/Diary/10-Fascinating-Things-About-Charles-Taylor 10 Fascinating Things About Charles Taylor] by ''The Young Turks''\n* [https://www.pbs.org/wgbh/pages/frontline/firestone-and-the-warlord/ Firestone and the Warlord \u2013 Frontline, PBS]\\\n* [https://www.nytimes.com/topic/person/charles-taylor Charles Taylor] collected news and commentary at [[The New York Times]]\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-off}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Ruth Perry]]|as=Chairperson of the Council of State of Liberia}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[President of Liberia]]|years=1997\u20132003}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Moses Blah]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{LiberianPresidents}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Taylor, Charles}}\n[[Category:1948 births]]\n[[Category:20th-century criminals]]\n[[Category:21st-century criminals]]\n[[Category:20th-century politicians]]\n[[Category:21st-century politicians]]\n[[Category:African warlords]]\n[[Category:Americo-Liberian people]]\n[[Category:Bentley University alumni]]\n[[Category:Blood diamonds]]\n[[Category:Escapees from United States federal government detention]]\n[[Category:Fugitives wanted by the United States]]\n[[Category:Heads of state convicted of war crimes]]\n[[Category:Liberian exiles]]\n[[Category:Liberian expatriates in Nigeria]]\n[[Category:Liberian people convicted of crimes against humanity]]\n[[Category:Liberian people convicted of murder]]\n[[Category:Liberian people convicted of war crimes]]\n[[Category:Liberian people imprisoned abroad]]\n[[Category:Liberian people of Gola descent]]\n[[Category:Liberian rebels]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:National Patriotic Party politicians]]\n[[Category:People convicted by the Special Court for Sierra Leone]]\n[[Category:People convicted of crimes against humanity]]\n[[Category:People convicted of rape]]\n[[Category:People extradited from Liberia]]\n[[Category:People extradited to Sierra Leone]]\n[[Category:People extradited from Sierra Leone]]\n[[Category:People from Montserrado County]]\n[[Category:Politicians convicted of murder]]\n[[Category:Politicians convicted of sex offences]]\n[[Category:Presidents of Liberia]]\n[[Category:Prisoners and detainees of England and Wales]]\n[[Category:Liberian politicians convicted of crimes]]\n[[Category:Genocide perpetrators]]\n[[Category:Heads of regimes who were later imprisoned]]\n", "text_old": "{{redirect|Charles G. Taylor|the English cricketer|Charles Taylor (cricketer, born 1816)|the Welsh rugby union player|Charles Taylor (rugby union)|the American baseball player|Chuck Taylor (baseball)}}\n{{short description|Liberian former politician who was the 22nd President of Liberia}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2013}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|name          = Charles Taylor\n|image         = President Charles Taylor.png\n|birth_name    = Charles McArthur Taylor\n|office        = 22nd [[President of Liberia]]\n|term_start    = 2 August 1997\n|alt = Taylor seated at a desk\n|term_end      = 11 August 2003\n|vicepresident = {{plainlist|\n*[[Enoch Dogolea]]\n*[[Moses Blah]]}}\n|predecessor   = [[Ruth Perry]] (Chairperson of the Council of State)\n|successor     = [[Moses Blah]]\n|birth_date    = {{Birth date and age|df=yes|1948|1|28}}\n|birth_place   = [[Arthington, Liberia|Arthington]], [[Liberia]]\n|party         = [[People's Redemption Council]] (expelled in 1983) <br>[[National Patriotic Party|National Patriotic]]\n|spouse        = {{ubl|{{marriage|Enid Tupee Taylor|1979|1997}}|{{marriage|[[Jewel Taylor|Jewel Howard]]|1997|2006|end=div}}}}\n|children      = 14, including [[Charles McArther Emmanuel]]\n|alma_mater    = [[Bentley University]] \n|occupation = [[Warlord]], Former [[Head of State]]\n|allegiance = {{LBR}}\n| rank = [[Commander]]\n| commands = [[Liberian Army]]\n| battles = *[[First Liberian Civil War]] \n*[[Sierra Leone Civil War]]\n*[[Second Liberian Civil War]] \n}}\n\n'''Charles McArthur Ghankay Taylor''' (born 28 January 1948) is a [[Liberian people|Liberian]] former politician and convicted war criminal who served as the [[President of Liberia#List of Presidents of Liberia|22nd]] [[President of Liberia]] from 2 August 1997 until his resignation on 11 August 2003.<ref name=\"allafricatheend\">{{cite news | first=Ofeibea | last=Quist-Arcton | title=Liberia: Charles Ghankay Taylor, Defiant And Passionate To The End | date=11 August 2003 | publisher=allAfrica.com | url =http://allafrica.com/stories/200308111235.html | accessdate =18 January 2008 }}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=Agencies|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2003/aug/11/westafrica|title=Liberian president Taylor steps down|date=2003-08-11|work=The Guardian|access-date=2020-02-28|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref>\n\nBorn in [[Arthington, Liberia|Arthington]], [[Montserrado County]], [[Liberia]], Taylor earned a degree at [[Bentley College]] in the United States before returning to Liberia to work in the government of [[Samuel Doe]]. After being removed for [[embezzlement]], he eventually arrived in [[Great Socialist People's Libyan Arab Jamahiriya|Libya]], where he was trained as a [[guerrilla fighter]]. He returned to Liberia in 1989 as the head of a Libyan-backed rebel group, the [[National Patriotic Front of Liberia]], to overthrow the Doe government, initiating the [[First Liberian Civil War]] (1989\u201396). Following Doe's execution, Taylor gained control of a large portion of the country and became one of the most prominent [[warlord]]s in Africa.<ref name=\"economistjustice\">{{cite news |url= http://www.economist.com/world/africa/displaystory.cfm?story_id=9262468 |title= Justice at last?|accessdate=5 August 2007|date= 31 May 2007|work=The Economist}}</ref> Following a peace deal that ended the war, Taylor was elected president in the [[1997 Liberian general election|1997 general election]].<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.nytimes.com/2000/12/07/world/in-ruined-liberia-its-despoiler-sits-pretty.html | work=The New York Times | first=Norimitsu | last=Onishi | title=In Ruined Liberia, Its Despoiler Sits Pretty | date=7 December 2000}}</ref>\n\nDuring his term of office, Taylor was accused of [[war crimes]] and [[crimes against humanity]] as a result of his involvement in the [[Sierra Leone Civil War]] (1991\u20132002). Domestically, opposition to his government grew, culminating in the outbreak of the [[Second Liberian Civil War]] (1999\u20132003). By 2003, Taylor had lost control of much of the countryside and was formally indicted by the [[Special Court for Sierra Leone]]. That year, he resigned, as a result of growing international pressure, and went into [[exile]] in [[Nigeria]]. In 2006, the newly elected President, [[Ellen Johnson Sirleaf]], formally requested his extradition. He was detained by UN authorities in Sierra Leone and then at the [[Hague Penitentiary Institution|Penitentiary Institution Haaglanden]] in [[The Hague]], awaiting trial by the Special Court.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.time.com/time/world/article/0,8599,1910365,00.html | work=TIME | title= 'Lies and Rumors': Liberia's Charles Taylor on the Stand| date=14 July 2009 |accessdate=14 July 2009 | first=Leo | last=Cendrowicz}}</ref> He was found guilty in April 2012 of all eleven charges levied by the Special Court, including terror, murder and rape.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-africa-17864387 |work=BBC | title= Taylor Sierra Leone war crimes verdict welcomed | date= 26 April 2012 | accessdate=1 May 2012}}</ref> In May 2012, Taylor was sentenced to 50 years in prison. Reading the sentencing statement, Presiding Judge [[Richard Lussick]] said: \"The accused has been found responsible for aiding and abetting as well as planning some of the most heinous and brutal crimes in recorded human history.\"<ref>{{cite news | url=http://edition.cnn.com/2012/05/30/world/africa/netherlands-taylor-sentencing/index.html |work=CNN | title=Charles Taylor sentenced to 50 years for war crimes | date= 31 May 2012 | accessdate=9 June 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nTaylor was born in [[Arthington, Liberia|Arthington]], a town near the capital of [[Monrovia]], [[Liberia]], on 28 January 1948, to Nelson and Bernice Taylor. He attended [[The Newman School]] in his early years. He took the name \"Ghankay\" later on, possibly to please and gain favor with indigenous Liberians.<ref name='contemporaryreviewreport'>{{cite news|first=Abiodun |last=Onadipe |title=Liberia: Taylor's first year report card. (President Charles Ghankay Taylor) |date=November 1998 |url=http://www.encyclopedia.com/doc/1G1-53450030.html |work=Contemporary Review |accessdate=18 January 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081205164053/http://www.encyclopedia.com/doc/1G1-53450030.html |archivedate=5 December 2008 }}</ref> His mother was a member of the [[Gola (ethnic group)|Gola]] ethnic group, part of the 95% of the people who are indigenous to Liberia. According to most reports, his father was an [[Americo-Liberian]] (a member of Liberia's narrow elite, descended from African-American colonists) who worked as a teacher, sharecropper, lawyer and judge.<ref>{{cite web|last=Burlij|first=Terence|title=A Profile of Charles Taylor|url=https://www.pbs.org/newshour/bb/africa/liberia/taylor-bio.html|work=PBS|publisher=Online NewsHour|accessdate=27 April 2012}}</ref>\n\nIn 1977, Taylor earned a degree at [[Bentley University]] in [[Waltham, Massachusetts]], United States.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.cnn.com/2013/04/26/world/africa/charles-taylor-fast-facts/index.html|title=Charles Taylor Fast Facts|last=Library|first=C. N. N.|website=CNN|access-date=2017-05-22}}</ref>\n\n==Government, imprisonment and escape==\nTaylor supported the [[People's Redemption Council|12 April 1980 coup]] led by [[Samuel Doe]], which resulted in the murder of President [[William R. Tolbert Jr.]] and seizure of power by Doe. Taylor was appointed to the position of Director General of the General Services Agency (GSA), a position that left him in charge of purchasing for the Liberian government. He was sacked in May 1983 for embezzling an estimated $1,000,000 and sending the funds to another bank account.\n\nTaylor fled to the United States but was arrested on 21 May 1984 by two [[United States Marshals Service|US Deputy Marshals]] in [[Somerville, Massachusetts]], on a warrant for extradition to face charges of embezzling $1 million of government funds while the GSA boss.<ref name=star>\"How Charles Taylor Escaped from Jail\". <nowiki>[</nowiki>[[Monrovia]]<nowiki>]</nowiki> ''Daily Star'', 1985-10-05: 10.</ref> Taylor fought extradition with the help of a legal team led by former [[Attorney General of the United States|US Attorney General]] [[Ramsey Clark]].  His lawyers' primary arguments before US District Magistrate Robert J. DeGiacomo stated that his alleged acts of lawbreaking in Liberia were political rather than criminal in nature and that the extradition treaty between the two republics had lapsed. Assistant United States Attorney [[Richard Gaylore Stearns|Richard G. Stearns]] argued that Liberia wished to charge Taylor with theft in office, rather than with political crimes. Stearns' arguments were reinforced by Liberian Justice Minister Jenkins Scott, who flew to the United States to testify at the proceedings.<ref>\"Taylor's Judgement Expected: Final Argument Advanced: Justice Minister Flies Back\". <nowiki>[</nowiki>[[Monrovia]]<nowiki>]</nowiki> ''Sunday Express'' 1984-09-09: 1/8.</ref> Taylor was detained in the [[Plymouth County Correctional Facility]].<ref name=star />\n\nOn 15 September 1985, Taylor and four other inmates escaped from the jail. Two days later, ''[[The Boston Globe]]'' reported that they sawed through a bar covering a window in a dormitory room, after which they lowered themselves {{convert|20|ft}} on knotted sheets and escaped into nearby woods by climbing a fence.<ref name=star />  Shortly thereafter, Taylor and two other escapees were met at nearby Jordan Hospital by Taylor's wife, Enid, and Taylor's sister-in-law, Lucia Holmes Toweh. They drove a getaway car to [[Staten Island]] in New York, where Taylor disappeared. All four of Taylor's fellow escapees, as well as Enid and Toweh, were later apprehended.{{citation needed|date=May 2012}}\n\nIn July 2009, Taylor claimed at his trial that US CIA agents had helped him escape from the maximum security prison in Boston in 1985. This was during his trial by the UN-backed Special Court for Sierra Leone in The Hague. The US Defense Intelligence Agency confirmed that Taylor first started working with US intelligence in the 1980s but refused to give details of his role or US actions, citing national security.<ref>[https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-africa-16627628 Charles Taylor 'worked' for CIA in Liberia], [[BBC]], 2012-01-19.  Accessed 4 June 2012.</ref><ref>[[Bryan Bender]], ''[[The Boston Globe]]'', 17 January 2012, [https://www.bostonglobe.com/metro/2012/01/17/mass-escapee-turned-liberian-dictator-had-spy-agency-ties/DGBhSfjxPVrtoo4WT95bBI/story.html \"Former Liberian dictator Charles Taylor had US spy agency ties\"], ''Boston Globe'', 17 January 2012</ref>\n\n===Civil war===\nTaylor escaped the United States without an issue. He then resurfaced in [[Great Socialist People's Libyan Arab Jamahiriya|Libya]] where he took part in militia training under [[Muammar Gaddafi]], becoming Gaddafi's prot\u00e9g\u00e9.<ref name=\"economistfall\">{{cite news |url= http://www.economist.com/world/international/displaystory.cfm?story_id=9441341 |title= How the mighty are falling | accessdate=17 July 2007 | date= 5 July 2007 |work=The Economist}}</ref> He later left Liberia and traveled to the [[Ivory Coast]], where he founded the [[National Patriotic Front of Liberia]] (NPFL).\n\nIn December 1989, Taylor launched a Gaddafi-funded armed uprising from the Ivory Coast into Liberia to overthrow the Doe regime, leading to the [[First Liberian Civil War]].<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/africa/8429962.stm \"Grim legacy of Liberia's most isolated town\"], ''BBC''</ref> By 1990, his forces controlled most of the country. That same year, [[Prince Johnson]], a senior commander of Taylor's NPFL, broke away and formed the [[Independent National Patriotic Front of Liberia]] (INPFL).\n\nIn September 1990, Johnson captured [[Monrovia]], depriving Taylor of outright victory. Johnson and his forces captured and [[torture]]d Doe to death, instigating a violent political fragmentation of the country.<ref name=MASK>{{cite book|last=Ellis|first=Stephen|title=The Mask of Anarchy: The Destruction of Liberia and the Religious Dimension of African Civil War 1999, 2007 |publisher=Hurst & Company|location=London, UK|isbn=1850654174|pages=1\u201316|year=1999}}</ref> The civil war turned into an [[ethnic conflict]], with seven factions among indigenous peoples and the Americo-Liberians fighting for control of Liberia's resources (especially iron ore, diamonds, timber, and rubber).\n\nAmos Sawyer alleges that Taylor\u2019s aims extended beyond Liberia\u2014that he wanted to re-establish the country as a regional power player.  Taylor's ambitions, held both during the civil war period and into his presidency, resulted not only in domestic  Liberian conflict, but also to regional instability in the form of the [[Sierra Leone Civil War]] and unrest in the forest region of Guinea.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Sawyer|first=Amos|date=2004|title=Violent conflicts and governance challenges in West Africa: the case of the Mano River basin area|url=|journal=Journal of Modern African Studies|volume=42|issue=3|pages=437\u2013463|doi=10.1017/S0022278X04000266}}</ref>\n\nAccording to a 2 June 1999 article in ''[[The Virginian-Pilot]]'',<ref>Sizemore, Bill. [https://groups.google.com/group/misc.activism.progressive/browse_thread/thread/dca03c4012450e0c/f230a667e3ff73d5].  \"Robertson, Liberian Leader Hope to Strike Gold in Coastal Africa\"], ''The Virginian-Pilot''. 2 June 1999.</ref> Taylor had extensive business dealings with American [[televangelist]] [[Pat Robertson]] during the civil war. He gave Robertson the rights to mine for [[diamonds]] in Liberia. According to two [[Operation Blessing]] pilots who reported this incident in 1994 to the Commonwealth of [[Virginia]] for investigation, Robertson used his Operation Blessing aeroplanes to haul diamond-mining equipment to his new mines in Liberia, while telling his ''[[700 Club]]'' viewers that the planes were sending relief supplies to the victims of the [[genocide in Rwanda]]. The subsequent investigation by the Commonwealth of [[Virginia]] concluded that Robertson diverted his ministry's donations to the Liberian diamond-mining operation. [[Attorney General of Virginia]] [[Mark Earley]] blocked any prosecution of Robertson, as the relief supplies were also sent.<ref name='nationrobertson'>{{cite news | first=Max | last=Blumenthal | title= Pat Robertson's Katrina Cash | date=7 September 2005 | url =http://www.thenation.com/doc/20050919/blumenthal | work =The Nation Online | accessdate =19 January 2008 }}</ref>\n\n==Presidency==\nAfter the official end of the civil war in 1996, Taylor ran for president in the [[1997 Liberian general election|1997 general election]]. He campaigned on the notorious slogan \"He killed my ma, he killed my pa, but I will vote for him.\"<ref name='guardianwar'>{{cite news | first=Sarah | last=Left | title=War in Liberia | date=4 August 2003 | url =https://www.theguardian.com/westafrica/story/0,,1008084,00.html |work=The Guardian | accessdate =18 January 2008 | location=London}}</ref>\n\nThe elections were overseen by the United Nations' peacekeeping mission, [[United Nations Observer Mission in Liberia]], along with a contingent from the [[Economic Community of West African States]].<ref name='unomilsite'>{{cite web|url=https://www.un.org/Depts/dpko/dpko/co_mission/unomil.htm |title=UNOMIL |accessdate=18 January 2008 |year=2001 |publisher= Information Technology Section/Department of Public Information }}</ref> Taylor won the election in a landslide, garnering 75 percent of the vote.  Although the election was widely reckoned as free and fair by international observers, Taylor had a huge advantage going into it. He had already taken over the former state radio station and took advantage of its access. Additionally, there was widespread fear in the country that Taylor would resume the war if he lost.\n\nDuring his time in office, Taylor cut the size of the [[Armed Forces of Liberia]], dismissing 2,400\u20132,600 former personnel, many of whom were ethnic [[Krahn]] brought in by former President Doe to give advantage to his people.<ref>Adebayo, ''Liberia's Civil War'', International Peace Academy, 2002, p.235</ref> In its place, Taylor installed the [[Anti-Terrorist Unit (Liberia)|Anti-Terrorist Unit]], the Special Operations Division of the [[Law enforcement in Liberia|Liberian National Police]] (LNP), which he used as his own private army.\n\nDuring his presidency, Taylor was alleged to have been involved directly in the [[Sierra Leone Civil War]]. He was accused of aiding the rebel [[Revolutionary United Front]] (RUF) through weapon sales in exchange for [[blood diamond]]s. Due to a UN embargo against arms sales to Liberia at the time, these weapons were largely purchased on the [[black market]] through arms smugglers such as [[Viktor Bout]].<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/asia/merchant-of-death-who-armed-tyrants-fights-extradition-to-us-1208489.html | title='Merchant of Death' who armed tyrants fights extradition to US | date=23 December 2008 |work=The Independent   | location=London | first=Andy | last=McSmith}}</ref> Taylor was charged with aiding and abetting RUF atrocities against civilians, which left many thousands dead or mutilated, with unknown numbers of people abducted and tortured. He was also accused of assisting the RUF in the recruitment of [[child soldiers]]. In addition to aiding the RUF in these acts, Taylor reportedly personally directed RUF operations in Sierra Leone.<ref>''Merchant of Death: Money, Guns, Planes, and the Man Who Makes War Possible''. Douglas Farah, Stephen Braun. p. 167</ref>\n\nTaylor obtained spiritual and other advice from the evangelist [[K.A. Paul|Kilari Anand Paul]].<ref name='newyorkerpersuader'>{{cite news | first=William | last=Finnegan | title=The Persuader | date= 1 September 2003 | url =https://www.newyorker.com/archive/2003/09/01/030901ta_talk_finnegan?printable=true | work =The New Yorker | accessdate =19 January 2008}}</ref> As president, he was known for his flamboyant style.<ref name=Preacher/> Upon being charged by the UN of being a gunrunner and diamond smuggler during his presidency, Taylor appeared in all-white robes and begged God for forgiveness, while denying the charges.<ref name=Preacher>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/africa/2963086.stm|title=Charles Taylor \u2013 preacher, warlord, president|newspaper=BBC News|date=13 July 2009}}</ref> He was reported to have said that \"Jesus Christ was accused of being a murderer in his time.\"<ref name=Preacher/>\n\n===Rebellion and indictment===\nIn 1999, a rebellion against Taylor began in northern Liberia, led by a group calling itself [[Liberians United for Reconciliation and Democracy]] (LURD). This group was frequently accused of atrocities, and is thought to have been backed by the government of neighboring [[Guinea]].<ref name='humanrightswatchlurd'>{{cite journal|title=Back to the Brink|journal=Human Rights Watch Report|date=1 May 2002|volume=14|issue=A |url=https://www.hrw.org/reports/2002/liberia/|accessdate=18 January 2008}}</ref> This uprising signaled the beginning of the [[Second Liberian Civil War]].\n\nBy early 2003, LURD had gained control of northern Liberia. That year, a second [[Ivory Coast|Ivorian]]-backed rebel group, [[Movement for Democracy in Liberia]] (MODEL), emerged in southern Liberia and achieved rapid successes.<ref name='humanrightswatchmodel'>{{cite news | title=Liberia |date=January 2004 | url =https://www.hrw.org/english/docs/2004/01/29/liberi7246.htm | work =Briefing to the 60th Session of the UN Commission on Human Rights | accessdate =18 January 2008 }}</ref> By the summer, Taylor's government controlled only about a third of Liberia: Monrovia and the central part of the country. More than one-third of the total population lived in this area.\n\nOn 7 March 2003, the [[Special Court for Sierra Leone]] (SCSL) issued a [[sealed indictment]] for Taylor.<ref>[http://www.sc-sl.org/CASES/ProsecutorvsCharlesTaylor/tabid/107/Default.aspx \"The Prosecutor vs. Charles Ghankay Taylor\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120604005902/http://www.sc-sl.org/CASES/ProsecutorvsCharlesTaylor/tabid/107/Default.aspx |date=4 June 2012 }}, The Special Court for Sierra Leone. Retrieved 26 March 2010</ref>  Earlier that year, Liberian forces had killed [[Sam Bockarie]], a leading member of the RUF in Sierra Leone, in a shootout under Taylor's orders. Some have claimed that Taylor ordered Bockarie killed in order to prevent the leader from testifying against him at the SCSL.<ref name='perspective'>{{cite news | title=The Mysterious Death of a Fugitive | date=7 May 2003 | work=The Perspective |location=Atlanta, Georgia, United States | url =http://www.theperspective.org/fugitivebockarie.html | accessdate =18 January 2008 }}</ref>\n\nIn June 2003, Alan White, the Prosecutor to the Special Court unsealed the indictment and announced publicly that Taylor was charged with war crimes. The indictment asserted that Taylor created and backed the RUF rebels in Sierra Leone, who were accused of a range of atrocities, including the use of [[child soldier]]s.<ref name='taylorindictment'>{{Cite book| first=David M. | last=Crane| contribution=CASE NO. SCSL \u2013 03 \u2013 I| title=The Special Court for Sierra Leone| editor-first=| editor-last=| publisher=United Nations and the Government of Sierra Leone| place=Freetown, Sierra Leone| date=3 March 2003| id= | contribution-url=http://www.sc-sl.org/Documents/SCSC-03-01-I-001.html | accessdate=18 January 2008 }}</ref><ref name=\"Female Victim\">{{cite web|url=https://www.liberianobserver.com/news/victim-pleads-for-war-crimes-court/ |title=Female Victim Pleads for War Crimes Court |author= Joaquin M. Sendolo |work=[[Liberian Observer]] |date=21 March 2018 |accessdate=21 June 2018 }}</ref> The Prosecutor also said that Taylor's administration had harbored members of [[Al-Qaeda]] sought in connection with the 1998 bombings of U.S. embassies in [[Kenya]] and [[Tanzania]].<ref>{{cite news| url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/africa/4577547.stm|publisher=BBC| date=24 May 2005 | title=UN pressed over Liberia's Taylor| author=Susannah Price | accessdate=2 January 2010}}</ref>\n\nThe indictment was unsealed during Taylor's official visit to [[Ghana]], where he was participating in peace talks with MODEL and LURD officials. As result, the possibility arose that Taylor might be arrested by Ghanaian authorities; in response, Taylor's chief bodyguard and military commander [[Benjamin Yeaten]] threatened to execute Ghanians who lived in Liberia, deterring Ghana's government from taking action.<ref name=\"Female Victim\"/> With the backing of South African president [[Thabo Mbeki]] and against the urging of [[Sierra Leone]] president [[Ahmad Tejan Kabbah]], Ghana consequently declined to detain Taylor, who returned to Monrovia.\n\n===Resignation===\nDuring Taylor's absence for the peace talks in Ghana, the U.S. government was alleged to have urged [[Vice President of Liberia|Vice President]] [[Moses Blah]] to seize power.<ref name='bbcblahprofile'>{{cite news | first=Jonathan | last=Paye-Layleh | title=Profile: Moses Blah | date=10 August 2003 | url =http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/world/africa/3140063.stm |work=BBC News | accessdate =18 January 2008 }}</ref> Upon his return, Taylor briefly dismissed Blah from his post, only to reinstate him a few days later.\n\nIn July 2003, LURD initiated a siege of Monrovia, and several bloody battles were fought as Taylor's forces halted rebel attempts to capture the city. The pressure on Taylor increased as U.S. President [[George W. Bush]] twice that month stated that Taylor \"must leave Liberia\". On 9 July, Nigerian President [[Olusegun Obasanjo]] offered Taylor [[exile]] in his country on the condition that Taylor stay out of Liberian politics.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.cnn.com/2003/WORLD/africa/07/09/liberia/ | title=Nigeria would shield Taylor from trial|publisher=CNN|date=10 July 2003 | accessdate=28 April 2010}}</ref>\n\nTaylor insisted that he would resign only if U.S. [[peacekeeping]] troops were deployed to Liberia. Bush publicly called upon Taylor to resign and leave the country in order for any American involvement to be considered. Meanwhile, several African states, in particular the [[Economic Community of West African States]] (ECOWAS) under the leadership of Nigeria, sent troops under the banner of [[ECOMIL]] to Liberia.<ref name=\"nytimesnigeria\">{{cite news | first=Felicity | last=Barringer | title= Nigeria Readies Peace Force for Liberia; Battles Go On | date=24 July 2003 | url =https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9C0CE5D6153FF937A15754C0A9659C8B63 | work =The New York Times | accessdate =18 January 2008 }}</ref>\n\nLogistical support was provided by a California company called [[Pacific Architects & Engineers|PAE]] Government Services Inc., which was given a $10 million contract by the [[U.S. State Department]].<ref name=\"nytimesnigeria\" /> On 6 August, a 32-member U.S. military assessment team were deployed as a liaison with the ECOWAS troops,<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.cnn.com/2003/WORLD/africa/07/07/liberia/ | title=Liberia's Taylor not ready to leave| date=7 July 2003|publisher=CNN | accessdate=28 April 2010}}</ref> landing from the 26th [[Marine Expeditionary Unit]], commanded by Colonel A.P. Frick, from three U.S. Navy amphibious ships waiting off the Liberian coast.\n\nOn 10 August, Taylor appeared on national television to announce that he would resign the following day and hand power to Vice President Blah. He harshly criticized the United States in his [[farewell address]], saying that the [[Presidency of George W. Bush|Bush administration]]'s insistence that he leave the country would hurt Liberia.<ref name=\"allafricatheend\" /> On 11 August, Taylor resigned, with Blah serving as president until a transitional government was established on 14 October. [[Ghana]]ian President [[John Kufuor]], South African President [[Thabo Mbeki]], and [[Mozambique|Mozambican]] President [[Joaquim Chissano]], all representing African regional councils, were present at his announcement. The U.S. brought [[Joint Task Force Liberia]]'s [[Amphibious Ready Group]] of three warships with 2,300 [[United States Marine Corps|Marines]] into view of the coast. Taylor flew to Nigeria, where the Nigerian government provided houses for him and his entourage in [[Calabar]].\n\n==Exile==\nIn November 2003, the [[United States Congress]] passed a bill that included a reward offer of two million dollars for Taylor's capture. While the peace agreement had guaranteed Taylor safe exile in Nigeria, it also required that he refrain from influencing Liberian politics. His critics said he disregarded this prohibition.  On 4 December, [[Interpol]] issued a [[red notice]] regarding Taylor, suggesting that countries had a duty to arrest him. Taylor was placed on Interpol's [[Most Wanted list]], declaring him wanted for [[crimes against humanity]] and breaches of the 1949 [[Fourth Geneva Convention|Geneva Convention]], and noting that he should be considered dangerous. Nigeria stated it would not submit to Interpol's demands, agreeing to deliver Taylor to Liberia only in the event that the President of Liberia requested his return.\n\nOn 17 March 2006, [[Ellen Johnson Sirleaf]], the newly elected President of Liberia, submitted an official request to Nigeria for Taylor's [[extradition]]. This request was granted on 25 March, whereby Nigeria agreed to release Taylor to stand trial in the [[Special Court for Sierra Leone]] (SCSL). Nigeria agreed only to release Taylor and not to extradite him, as no [[extradition treaty]] existed between the two countries.\n\n===Disappearance and arrest===\nThree days after Nigeria announced its intent to transfer Taylor to Liberia, the leader disappeared from the seaside villa where he had been living in exile.<ref>{{cite news| author=Polgreen, Lydia| title=Nigeria Says Ex-President of Liberia Has Disappeared| journal=The New York Times| date=29 March 2006| url=https://nytimes.com/2006/03/29/international/africa/29liberia.html}}</ref> A week before that, Nigerian authorities had taken the unusual step of allowing local press to accompany census takers into Taylor\u2019s Calabar compound.\n\nNigerian President [[Olusegun Obasanjo]] was scheduled to meet with President Bush less than 48 hours after Taylor was reported missing. Speculation ensued that Bush would refuse to meet with Obasanjo if Taylor were not apprehended. Less than 12 hours prior to the scheduled meeting between the two heads of state, Taylor was reported apprehended en route to Liberia.\n\nOn 29 March, Taylor tried to cross the border into [[Cameroon]] through the border town of Gamboru in northeastern Nigeria. His [[Range Rover]] with Nigerian diplomatic plates was stopped by border guards, and Taylor's identity was eventually established. [[United States Department of State|US State Department]] staff later reported that significant amounts of cash and heroin were found in the vehicle.\n\nUpon his arrival at [[Roberts International Airport]] in [[Harbel]], Liberia, Taylor was arrested and handcuffed by LNP officers, who immediately transferred responsibility for the custody of Taylor to the [[United Nations Mission in Liberia]] (UNMIL). Irish UNMIL soldiers escorted Taylor aboard a UN helicopter to [[Freetown]], Sierra Leone, where he was delivered to the SCSL.\n\n==Trial==\n[[File:Monrovia news board 2008.jpeg|thumb|Newsboard documenting the Charles Taylor case]]\nThe SCSL prosecutor originally indicted Taylor on 3 March 2003 on a 17-counts for [[war crimes]] and crimes against humanity committed during the conflict in Sierra Leone. On 16 March 2006, a SCSL judge gave leave to amend the indictment against Taylor. Under the amended indictment, Taylor was charged with 11 counts. At Taylor's initial appearance before the court on 3 April 2006, he entered a plea of not guilty.<ref name='spslIndictment'>{{cite news | first= Desmond, QC, Chief Prosecutor, Special Court for Sierra Leone | last=de Silva | title=Chief Prosecutor Announces the Arrival of Charles Taylor at the Special Court | date=29 March 2006 | url =http://www.sc-sl.org/Press/prosecutor-032906.pdf | work =Press Release from the Special Court for Sierra Leone | accessdate =19 January 2008 |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20071201194256/http://www.sc-sl.org/Press/prosecutor-032906.pdf <!-- Bot retrieved archive --> |archivedate = 1 December 2007}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=THE PROSECUTOR OF THE SPECIAL COURT V. CHARLES GHANKAY TAYLOR Monday, 4 June 2007|url=http://www.sc-sl.org/LinkClick.aspx?fileticket=SA/7CCB4VCc=&tabid=160|publisher=Special Court of Sierra Leone|accessdate=6 December 2013|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130521023914/http://www.sc-sl.org/LinkClick.aspx?fileticket=SA%2F7CCB4VCc%3D&tabid=160|archivedate=21 May 2013|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nIn early June 2006, the decision on whether to hold Taylor's trial in Freetown or in [[Leidschendam]] had not yet been made by the new SCSL president, [[George Gelaga King]]. King's predecessor had pushed for the trial to be held abroad because of fear that a local trial would be politically destabilizing in an area where Taylor still had influence.<ref name=\"economistjustice\"/>  The Appeals Chamber of the Special Court dismissed a motion by Taylor's defence team, who argued that their client could not get a fair trial there and also wanted the Special Court to withdraw the request to move the trial to Leidschendam.<ref name='newafricantrial'>{{cite news | title =Will Taylor Get a Fair Trial? | date =February 2007 | url =http://www.fortaylor.net/article17.htm | work =New African (Sierra Leone) | accessdate =19 January 2008 | url-status =dead | archiveurl =https://web.archive.org/web/20071026003901/http://www.fortaylor.net/article17.htm | archivedate =26 October 2007 | df =dmy-all }}</ref><ref name=\"IRIN where\">{{cite news | title=SIERRA LEONE: Decision on Taylor trial venue rests with head of Special Court | date=19 January 2008 | publisher=Irin News | url =http://www.irinnews.org/report.aspx?reportid=59190 | work =New African (Sierra Leone) | accessdate =19 January 2008 }}</ref>\n\nOn 15 June 2006, the [[British government]] agreed to jail Taylor in the United Kingdom in the event that he was convicted by the SCSL. This fulfilled a condition laid down by the [[Dutch government]], which had stated it was willing to host the trial but would not jail him if convicted. British Foreign Minister [[Margaret Beckett]] stated that new legislation would be required to accommodate this arrangement.<ref name='bbcagrees'>{{cite news | title=UK Agrees to Jail Charles Taylor | date=15 June 2006 | url =http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/world/africa/5082664.stm |work=BBC News | accessdate =19 January 2008 }}</ref> This legislation came in the form of the International Tribunals (Sierra Leone) Act 2007. <ref>http://www.legislation.gov.uk/ukpga/2007/7/enacted</ref> While awaiting his extradition to the [[Netherlands]], Taylor was held in a UN jail in Freetown.<ref name='CBCjail'>{{cite news | title=Charles Taylor jailed in Sierra Leone | date=29 March 2006 | url =https://www.cbc.ca/news/world/charles-taylor-jailed-in-sierra-leone-1.589212 | work =CBC News | accessdate =19 January 2008 }}</ref>\n\nOn 16 June 2006, the [[UNSC|United Nations Security Council]] agreed unanimously to allow Taylor to be sent to Leidschendam for trial; on 20 June 2006, Taylor was extradited and flown to [[Rotterdam Airport]] in the Netherlands. He was taken into custody and held in the detention centre of the [[International Criminal Court]], located in the [[Scheveningen]] section of The Hague.<ref name='forum'>{{cite news|first=Lansana |last=Fofana |title=Mixed Feelings over Charles Taylor's Transfer to The Hague |date=20 June 2006 |url=http://globalpolicy.igc.org/intljustice/wanted/2006/0620mixedfeelings.htm |work=Global Policy Forum |accessdate=19 January 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090107175200/http://globalpolicy.igc.org/intljustice/wanted/2006/0620mixedfeelings.htm |archivedate=7 January 2009 }}</ref> The Association for the Legal Defence of Charles G. Taylor was established in June 2006 to assist in his legal defence.\n\nWhen Taylor's trial opened on 4 June 2007, Taylor boycotted the proceeding and was not present. Through a letter that was read by his attorney to the court, he justified his absence by alleging that at that moment he was not ensured a fair and impartial trial.<ref>{{cite news | last = Hudson | first = Alexandra  | title = Taylor absent as trial gets underway |work=IOL| date = 4 June 2007 | url = http://www.int.iol.co.za/index.php?set_id=1&click_id=86&art_id=nw20070604110955292C367300\n| accessdate =4 June 2007}}</ref>\n\nOn 20 August 2007, Taylor's defence, now led by [[Courtenay Griffiths]], obtained a postponement of the trial until 7 January 2008.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/africa/6954627.stm |title=Taylor trial delayed until 2008 |accessdate=20 August 2007 |work=BBC News  | date=20 August 2007}}</ref> During the trial, the chief prosecutor alleged that a key insider witness who testified against Taylor went into hiding after being threatened for giving evidence against Taylor.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://edition.cnn.com/2008/WORLD/africa/02/28/Taylor.warcrimes.ap/index.html |title=Witness in Taylor war crimes trial in hiding after threats |accessdate=28 February 2008 |work=CNN |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20080229224224/http://edition.cnn.com/2008/WORLD/africa/02/28/Taylor.warcrimes.ap/index.html <!-- Bot retrieved archive --> |archivedate = 29 February 2008}}</ref> Furthermore, Joseph \"Zigzag\" Marzah, a former military commander, testified that Charles Taylor celebrated his new-found status during the civil war by ordering human sacrifice, including the killings of Taylor's opponents and allies that were perceived to have betrayed Taylor, and by having a pregnant woman buried alive in sand.<ref>\"[http://www.aljazeera.com/news/africa/2008/03/200852512151608819.html \"Shock testimony at Taylor trial\"]. ''[[Al Jazeera]]''.</ref> Marzah also accused Taylor of forcing [[cannibalism]] on his soldiers in order to terrorize their enemies.<ref>\"[http://www.cnn.com/2008/WORLD/africa/03/13/warcrimes.taylor.ap/index.html Top aide testifies Taylor ordered soldiers to eat victims].\" ''[[CNN]]''.</ref>\n\nIn January 2009, the prosecution finished presenting its evidence against Taylor and closed its case on 27 February 2009. On 4 May 2009, a defence motion for a judgment on acquittal was dismissed, and arguments for Taylor's defence began in July 2009.<ref>Winter, Renate. \"Foreword,\" [http://www.sc-sl.org/LinkClick.aspx?fileticket=%2fuI3lqaO5D0%3d&tabid=53 ''Sixth Annual Report of the President of the Special Court for Sierra Leone: June 2008 to May 2009''] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120227083926/http://www.sc-sl.org/LinkClick.aspx?fileticket=%2FuI3lqaO5D0%3D&tabid=53 |date=27 February 2012 }}. Retrieved 11 January 2010.</ref> Taylor testified in his own defence from July through November 2009.<ref>[[Associated Press]]. [https://www.nytimes.com/aponline/2010/01/11/world/AP-EU-War-Crimes-Taylor.html \"Taylor: I Didn't Know Sierra Leone Rebel Pre-1991\"], ''The New York Times'', 11 January 2010. Retrieved 11 January 2010.</ref> The defence rested its case on 12 November 2010, with closing arguments set for early February 2011.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://edition.cnn.com/2010/WORLD/africa/11/12/liberia.taylor.trial/?hpt=T2|title=Charles Taylor's team rests case in war crimes trial|accessdate=14 November 2010|date=12 November 2010|work=CNN}}</ref>\n\nOn 8 February 2011, the trial court ruled in a 2\u20131 decision that it would not accept Taylor's trial summary, as the summary had not been submitted by the 14 January deadline. In response, Taylor and his counsel boycotted the trial and refused an order by the court to begin closing arguments. This boycott came soon after the [[United States diplomatic cables leak|2010 leak of American diplomatic cables]] by [[WikiLeaks]], in which the United States discussed the possibility of extraditing Taylor for prosecution in the United States in the event of his acquittal by the SCSL. Taylor's counsel cited the leaked cable and the court's decision as evidence of an international conspiracy against Taylor.<ref>{{cite news|last=Corder|first=Mike|title=Charles Taylor Boycotts End of War Crimes Trial|url=http://www.nbcnews.com/id/41478144|agency=Associated Press|newspaper=MSNBC|date=8 February 2011|accessdate=26 March 2012}}</ref>\n\nOn 3 March, the appeals court of the SCSL overturned the trial court's decision, ruling that as the trial court had not established that Taylor had been counseled by the court and personally indicated his intent to waive his right to a trial summary, Taylor's [[due process]] rights would be violated by preventing him from submitting a trial summary. The appeals court ordered the trial court to accept the summary and set a date for the beginning of closing arguments.<ref>{{cite news|title=Judges allow Charles Taylor's closing arguments|url=https://www.google.com/hostednews/afp/article/ALeqM5hLGZ8fiXA0-Ni7zTLGVHFF8fSNOA?docId=CNG.5eda08e8eb1b42b79c577796fd7c8cba.9d1|agency=AFP|newspaper=Google News|date=3 March 2011|accessdate=4 March 2011}}</ref>  On 11 March, the closing arguments ended and it was announced that the court would begin the process to reach a verdict.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://english.aljazeera.net/news/europe/2011/03/2011311172946791811.html |title=Trial of Charles Taylor ends \u2013 Europe |publisher=Al Jazeera English |date= |accessdate=8 June 2013}}</ref>\n\n===Verdict===\nThe verdict was announced in Leidschendam on 26 April 2012.<ref>{{cite news | url= http://www.time.com/time/world/article/0,8599,2113215,00.html| work=TIME | title= Warlord Convicted: Liberia's Charles Taylor Found Guilty of War Crimes| date=26 April 2012| first=Leo| last=Cendrowicz}}</ref> The SCSL unanimously ruled that he was guilty of all 11 counts of \"aiding and abetting\" war crimes and crimes against humanity,<ref name=BBC305>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-africa-18259596 |title=Liberia ex-leader Charles Taylor get 50 years in jail |date=30 May 2012 |work=BBC News |accessdate=30 May 2012}}</ref> making him the first (former) head of state to be convicted by an international tribunal since [[Karl D\u00f6nitz]] at the [[Nuremberg Trials]]. Taylor was convicted of the following 11 charges:<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-africa-12391507 |title=The charges against Charles Taylor |date=8 February 2012 |work=BBC News |accessdate=30 May 2012}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Count\n! Crime\n! Type*\n! Ruling\n|-\n| colspan=\"4\"  style=\"text-align:center; background:#00d0d0;\"|Terrorising the civilian population and collective punishments\n|-\n| | 1\n| | Acts of terrorism\n| |WC\n|| Guilty\n|-\n| colspan=\"4\"  style=\"text-align:center; background:#00d0d0;\"|Unlawful killings\n|-\n||2\n||Murder\n||CAH\n||Guilty\n|-\n||3\n||Violence to life, health and physical or mental well-being of persons, in particular murder\n||WC\n||Guilty\n|-\n| colspan=\"4\"  style=\"text-align:center; background:#00d0d0;\"|Sexual violence\n|-\n||4\n||Rape\n||CAH\n||Guilty\n|-\n||5\n||Sexual slavery and any other form of sexual violence\n||CAH\n||Guilty\n|-\n||6\n|| Outrages upon personal dignity\n||WC\n||Guilty\n|-\n| colspan=\"4\"  style=\"text-align:center; background:#00d0d0;\"|Physical violence\n|-\n||7\n||Violence to life, health and physical or mental well-being of persons, in particular cruel treatment\n||WC\n||Guilty\n|-\n||8\n||Other inhumane acts\n||CAH\n||Guilty\n|-\n| colspan=\"4\"  style=\"text-align:center; background:#00d0d0;\"|Use of child soldiers\n|-\n||9\n||Conscripting or enlisting children under the age of 15 years into armed forces or groups, or using them to participate actively in hostilities\n||VIHL\n||Guilty\n|-\n| colspan=\"4\"  style=\"text-align:center; background:#00d0d0;\"|Abductions and forced labor\n|-\n||10\n||Enslavement\n||CAH\n||Guilty\n|-\n| colspan=\"4\"  style=\"text-align:center; background:#00d0d0;\"|Looting\n|-\n||11\n||[[Pillage]]\n||WC\n||Guilty\n|-\n| Colspan=4 | *Explanation of type of crime: {{plainlist|\n* CAH {{=}} [[Crimes against humanity]]\n* WC {{=}} Violation of Article 3 common to the Geneva Conventions and of Additional Protocol II (war crimes)\n* VIHL {{=}} Other serious violation of international humanitarian law}}\n|}\n\nAt his trial, Taylor claimed that he was a victim, denied the charges and compared his actions of torture and crimes against humanity to the actions of [[George W. Bush]] in the [[War on Terror]].<ref>{{cite news| url= http://articles.cnn.com/2012-05-16/africa/world_africa_netherlands-taylor-sentencing_1_war-crimes-liberian-president-charles-taylor-international-tribunal?_s=PM:AFRICA| work= CNN| title= In his last stand, Charles Taylor defends himself as a peacemaker| date= 16 May 2012| access-date= 21 May 2012| archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20120520235156/http://articles.cnn.com/2012-05-16/africa/world_africa_netherlands-taylor-sentencing_1_war-crimes-liberian-president-charles-taylor-international-tribunal?_s=PM:AFRICA| archive-date= 20 May 2012| url-status= dead| df= dmy-all}}</ref> Sentencing hearings commenced on 3 May<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cnbc.com/id/47286835/Prosecutors_seek_80_year_sentence_for_Charles_Taylor|title=Prosecutors seek 80-year sentence for Charles Taylor|date=3 May 2012|publisher=CNBC|accessdate=30 May 2012}}{{Dead link|date=November 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> and were announced on 30 May. Taylor was sentenced to 50 years in prison.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/news/world/ex-liberian-president-charles-taylor-sentenced-to-50-years-in-prison/article2447255/ |title=Globe & Mail article |location=Toronto |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120530103119/http://www.theglobeandmail.com/news/world/ex-liberian-president-charles-taylor-sentenced-to-50-years-in-prison/article2447255/ |archivedate=30 May 2012 }}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2012/may/30/charles-taylor-sentenced-50-years-war-crimes|title=Charles Taylor sentenced to 50 years in prison for war crimes|last=Bowcott|first=Owen|date=2012-05-30|work=The Guardian|access-date=2019-12-03|last2=agencies|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref> He was about 64 at the time. His sentence was upheld on appeal.<ref>[http://www.aljazeera.com/news/africa/2013/09/charles-taylor-appeal-verdict-due-20139266564497970.html \"Judges uphold Charles Taylor's jail sentence\"], Al Jazeera, 26 September 2013.</ref>\n\nSierra Leone's government described the sentence as \"a step forward as justice has been done, though the magnitude of the sentence is not commensurate with the atrocities committed\".<ref name=BBC305 />\n\nTaylor appealed against the verdict, but on 26 September 2013 Appeals Chamber of the Special Court confirmed his guilt and the penalty of 50 years in prison. On 15 October 2013 he was transferred to British custody, and began serving his sentence at [[HM Prison Frankland]] in County Durham, England.<ref>{{cite news|title=Ex-warlord Charles Taylor's family say he is being 'ill-treated' in British jail|newspaper=[[Telegraph Media Group|The Telegraph]]|location=[[London]]|date=2013-10-29|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/africaandindianocean/liberia/10412158/Ex-warlord-Charles-Taylors-family-say-he-is-being-ill-treated-in-British-jail.html|accessdate=2014-04-11}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Liberia's Charles Taylor transferred to UK|newspaper=[[BBC News]]|publisher=[[BBC]]|date=2013-10-15|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-africa-24537834|accessdate=2014-04-11}}</ref> Taylor's attorneys filed a motion to have him transferred to a prison in Rwanda,<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2013/09/27/world/africa/charles-taylor-sierra-leone-war-crimes-case.html?_r=0|title=50-Year Sentence Upheld for Ex-President of Liberia|date=26 September 2013| newspaper=The New York Times|accessdate=29 September 2013|first1=Marlise|last1=Simons|first2=Alan|last2=Cowell}}</ref> but in March 2015 the motion was denied and he was ordered to continue serving his sentence in the United Kingdom.<ref>[https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-32055482 \"Ex-Liberia President Charles Taylor to stay in UK prison\"] ''BBC News'', March 25, 2015. Retrieved December 30, 2015.</ref> In 2017 it was found that he had been making phone calls from the prison to provide guidance to the National Patriotic Party and threaten some of his enemies.<ref name=phone>{{cite magazine |date=24 February 2017 |title=Phone a Fiend |magazine=Private eye |publisher=Pressdram Ltd |issue=1438 |page=18  }}</ref>\n\n==Family==\nIn 1997 Taylor married [[Jewel Taylor]], with whom he has one son. She filed for divorce in 2005, citing her husband's exile in Nigeria and the difficulty of visiting him due to a UN travel ban on her.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.irinnews.org/report.aspx?reportid=57741|title=LIBERIA: Charles Taylor's wife has divorce petition granted|accessdate=31 July 2010|work=IRIN Africa|date=6 January 2006}}</ref> The divorce was granted in 2006. Jewel Taylor currently serves as the [[Vice President of Liberia]].\n\nPhillip Taylor, Taylor's son with Jewel, remained in Liberia following his father's extradition to the SCSL. He was arrested by Liberian police officials on 5 March 2011 and charged with attempted murder in connection with an assault on the son of an immigration officer who had assisted in Charles Taylor's extradition;<ref name=likefather>{{cite news|first=Edwin G.|last=Genoway|url=http://www.thenewdawnliberia.com/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=2891:like-father-like-sons&catid=25:politics&Itemid=59|title=Like Father, Like Sons|newspaper=The New Dawn|date=7 March 2011|accessdate=7 March 2011}}</ref> the mother of the victim claimed that Phillip Taylor had sworn vengeance against the immigration officer.  He was arrested at [[Buchanan, Liberia|Buchanan]] in [[Grand Bassa County]],<ref>{{cite news|last=Toe|first=Jerome W.|title=Charles Taylor's Son Arrested: For Attempted Murder|work=[[Liberian Observer|Daily Observer]]|date=7 March 2011|pages=1, 26}}</ref> allegedly while attempting to cross the border into the Ivory Coast.<ref name=likefather />\n\nTaylor has three children with his second wife Victoria Addison Taylor; the youngest, Charlize, was born in March 2010.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.csmonitor.com/World/Africa/2012/0425/In-Monrovia-Charles-Taylor-s-wife-awaits-his-verdict|first=Kate|last=Thomas|title=In Monrovia, Charles Taylor's wife awaits his verdict|work=Christian Science Monitor|date=25 April 2012|accessdate=25 July 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/africa/8564395.stm|title=Wife of war crimes suspect Charles Taylor gives birth|work=BBC News|date=12 March 2010|accessdate=25 July 2015}}</ref> In 2014, Victoria was denied a visa to visit her husband while he serves his sentence in the United Kingdom.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.gnnliberia.com/articles/2014/01/29/charles-taylor%E2%80%99s-wife-denied-visa-husband-celebrates-66th-birth-anniversary|title=Charles Taylor's Wife Denied Visa, As Husband Celebrates 66th Birth Anniversary behind Bars in UK|work=GNN Liberia|date=29 January 2014|accessdate=25 July 2015|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150725220343/http://www.gnnliberia.com/articles/2014/01/29/charles-taylor%E2%80%99s-wife-denied-visa-husband-celebrates-66th-birth-anniversary|archivedate=25 July 2015|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://frontpageafricaonline.com/index.php/news/899-no-access-to-family-taylor-s-wife-laments-after-uk-denies-visa|title=No access to family: Taylor's wife laments after UK denies visa|work=Front Page Africa|date=5 March 2014|accessdate=25 July 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150726003821/http://frontpageafricaonline.com/index.php/news/899-no-access-to-family-taylor-s-wife-laments-after-uk-denies-visa|archive-date=26 July 2015|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nTaylor also has another son, a U.S. citizen named [[Charles McArther Emmanuel]], born to his college girlfriend. Emmanuel was arrested in 2006 after entering the United States and was charged with three counts, including participation in torture while serving in the Anti-Terrorist Unit in Liberia during his father's presidency. The law that prosecuted Taylor was put in place in 1994, before \"extraordinary rendition\" in an attempt to prevent U.S. citizens from committing acts of torture overseas. To date, this is the only prosecuted case.<ref>\"[http://www.cnn.com/2008/CRIME/09/30/taylor.torture.trial.ap/index.html?iref=mpstoryview Ex-prisoner: Taylor's son laughed at torture\"] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081218050420/http://www.cnn.com/2008/CRIME/09/30/taylor.torture.trial.ap/index.html?iref=mpstoryview |date=18 December 2008 }}, ''[[CNN]]'', 30 September 2008.</ref> In October 2008, Emmanuel was convicted on all three counts and sentenced to 97 years in prison.<ref>Couwels, John. \"[http://www.cnn.com/2008/CRIME/10/30/taylor.torture.verdict/index.html Ex-Liberian president's son convicted of torture\"], ''[[CNN]]''. 30 October 2008.</ref>\n\n==In popular culture==\n* Taylor is a prominent character in the 2004 novel [[The Darling (novel)|''The Darling'']] by Russell Banks.\n* The character Andre Baptiste Sr. from the 2005 film ''[[Lord of War]]'' is partially based on Taylor.<ref>{{cite journal|journal=The Boston Globe|date=16 September 2005|first=Ty|last=Burr|title=Provocative 'War' Skillfully Takes Aim|pages=D1}}</ref>\n* Taylor appears in the 2008 documentary ''[[Pray the Devil Back to Hell]]''.\n\n==See also==\n\n* [[Exotic Tropic Timber Enterprises]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* {{Cite book |title=The Liberian Civil War |first=Mark |last=Huband |year=1998 |location=London |publisher=F. Cass |isbn=0-7146-4340-8 |url-access=registration |url=https://archive.org/details/isbn_9780714647852 }}\n* {{Cite book |title=Charles Taylor and Liberia: Ambition and Atrocity in Africa's Lone Star State |first=Colin |last=Waugh |year=2011 |location=London |publisher=Zed Books Ltd |isbn=978-184813-847-6 }}\n\n==External links==\n* Trial proceedings are available directly from: [https://web.archive.org/web/20080501184018/http://www.sc-sl.org/ the UN Special Court for Sierra Leone]''\n* [http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/africa/2963086.stm BBC profile of Charles Taylor]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20060322014022/http://jurist.law.pitt.edu/currentawareness/taylor.php Charles Taylor legal news and resources], [[JURIST]]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20060418014254/http://jurist.law.pitt.edu/forumy/2006/03/handing-over-charles-taylor-its-time.php Handing Over Charles Taylor: It's Time], [[JURIST]] (op-ed by David Crane, former Chief Prosecutor for the Special Court for Sierra Leone who signed the indictment for Charles Taylor)\n* [http://www.cnn.com/2006/WORLD/africa/03/25/taylor.liberia/index.html Nigeria agrees to hand Taylor over to Liberia]\n* [http://edition.cnn.com/2006/WORLD/africa/03/29/taylor.profile/index.html \"Charles Taylor: A wanted man\"], CNN, 29 March 2006.\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20080501184018/http://www.sc-sl.org/ Special Court for Sierra Leone]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20051115090137/http://www.trial-ch.org/trialwatch/profiles/en/facts/p98.html The trial of Charles Taylor \u2013 TRIAL WATCH]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20060510044646/http://www.usip.org/events/2006/0407_taylor.html Charles Taylor on Trial] [[U.S. Institute of Peace]], 7 April 2006 (Audio)\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20090723081243/http://www.theyoungturks.com/story/2009/7/16/650/03802/Diary/10-Fascinating-Things-About-Charles-Taylor 10 Fascinating Things About Charles Taylor] by ''The Young Turks''\n* [https://www.pbs.org/wgbh/pages/frontline/firestone-and-the-warlord/ Firestone and the Warlord \u2013 Frontline, PBS]\\\n* [https://www.nytimes.com/topic/person/charles-taylor Charles Taylor] collected news and commentary at [[The New York Times]]\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-off}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Ruth Perry]]|as=Chairperson of the Council of State of Liberia}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[President of Liberia]]|years=1997\u20132003}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Moses Blah]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{LiberianPresidents}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Taylor, Charles}}\n[[Category:1948 births]]\n[[Category:20th-century criminals]]\n[[Category:21st-century criminals]]\n[[Category:20th-century politicians]]\n[[Category:21st-century politicians]]\n[[Category:African warlords]]\n[[Catego